{"id":"clm_02cff8d43b2ba26e","text":"The infrastructure that would make the link measurable is being assembled: community-curated FAIR data commons and multi-site consortia with common data elements are demonstrating that pooled, reusable preclinical data are feasible, and metadata standards aligned to ARRIVE 2.0 are being retrofitted so that in vivo data become repurposable at all.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_02cff8d43b2ba26e","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"preclinical / in vivo research","model":"preclinical / in vivo research; FAIR data commons / metadata standards","outcome":"reusable pooled preclinical data feasibility","method":"common data elements / multi-site consortia; FAIR data commons / metadata standards"}}
{"id":"clm_02d1e252ed95def4","text":"Openness is increasingly framed as the price of the community's continued permission to do the work, yet the single most common barrier to communicating animal research is that the research harms animals — a barrier that unpublished, unusable results only raise, because they convert a defensible harm into an indefensible one.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_02d1e252ed95def4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_031df9d722100d7d","text":"The same low-quality signature recurs wherever it is measured, from ischaemic-preconditioning and renal-injury syntheses reporting sample-size calculations in 2% of studies, to gene-therapy, herbal, and stem-cell meta-analyses with median risk-of-bias scores of four to five out of ten, to pain, osteoporosis and glioma reviews whose universally positive effects rest on studies at high or unclear risk of bias.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_031df9d722100d7d","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal disease-model meta-analyses (broad)","model":"animal disease-model meta-analyses (broad)","outcome":"pervasive low quality","method":"risk-of-bias & sample-size reporting"}}
{"id":"clm_03ae035bc6eab4a6","text":"A prominent reanalysis argued the project contained three statistical errors and that, corrected for sampling error and power, the data are actually consistent with high reproducibility.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_03ae035bc6eab4a6","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_042943aa9ceefcc0","text":"Proof-of-concept studies have converged on which covariates matter most for matching a virtual to a concurrent control — sex, route of administration, fasting status and body weight at study initiation — and laboratories running harmonised developmental and reproductive toxicity studies are already being encouraged to plan VCG implementation.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_042943aa9ceefcc0","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0557a7fb753725ae","text":"An independent robustness study of a liver microphysiological system found appreciable within- and between-study variability that undercuts its high-throughput utility.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_0557a7fb753725ae","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"iPSC-hepatocyte liver MPS","model":"iPSC-hepatocyte liver MPS","outcome":"reproducibility of MPS readouts","method":"MPS robustness / high-throughput utility"}}
{"id":"clm_05e91174b6c2c4a0","text":"A theoretical result shows that when a uniformly most powerful test exists, strict frequentist Type I error control means external borrowing yields no power gain at all, and a companion analysis proves that insisting on Type I error control forces the elimination of any favourable borrowing of historical information.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_05e91174b6c2c4a0","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"no power gain under strict error control","method":"frequentist type I error control vs external borrowing"}}
{"id":"clm_05eb56c6114ab555","text":"The evidence is genuinely mixed: a Shank2 multicentre study found that rigorously harmonised protocols yielded highly replicable genotype and treatment effects across sites, which standardisation and heterogenisation advocates read in opposite ways.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_05eb56c6114ab555","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0645e8399c1c3bc1","text":"The construct matters as much as the number: the frequently cited figure that about a fifth of PLOS ONE data-availability statements name a repository is a statement about statement content, not a rate of usable availability, and near-universal statement compliance at PLOS and BMC coexisted with genuine repository links in only 20.8% and 12.2% of papers.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_0645e8399c1c3bc1","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"biomedical journals (PLOS/BMC)","outcome":"biomedical journals (PLOS/BMC); statement content vs usable availability","method":"data-availability-statement content vs repository linking"}}
{"id":"clm_066064b87182c4bd","text":"The human-relevance advantage is nonetheless partial: standard kidney organoids retain immature proximal tubules with limited transporter expression and off-target cell types, so nephrotoxicity readouts require enhanced protocols before they are reliable.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_066064b87182c4bd","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"hPSC kidney organoids (proximal-tubule maturity); nephrotoxicity readout reliability","model":"hPSC kidney organoids (proximal-tubule maturity)","outcome":"nephrotoxicity readout reliability","method":"organoid differentiation protocols"}}
{"id":"clm_069ca2d64382d8ed","text":"Non-publication remains the root waste: laboratory-animal researchers themselves estimate only about half of animal experiments are ever published.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_069ca2d64382d8ed","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"laboratory animal experiments","model":"laboratory animal experiments","outcome":"non-publication / research waste","method":"publication-rate estimation (opinion survey)"}}
{"id":"clm_079c2b65d84d95a5","text":"Organoids express clinically relevant transporters and enzymes that conventional cell lines lack, gut-on-chip and gastrointestinal microphysiological systems recover absorption and first-pass metabolism for oral-bioavailability prediction, and barrier chips reconstruct human blood–brain-barrier and gut physiology with in vivo-like permeability and inflammatory responses.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_079c2b65d84d95a5","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"intestinal & brain organoids, barrier chips; oral bioavailability, neuroinflammation modelling","model":"intestinal & brain organoids, barrier chips","outcome":"oral bioavailability, neuroinflammation modelling","method":"gut-on-chip, BBB-chip, MPS"}}
{"id":"clm_08356a318e2577ab","text":"Whole experiments vanish before publication: surveys of laboratory-animal researchers estimate that only about half of conducted experiments are ever published, empirical protocol-to-publication tracking finds a more optimistic but still incomplete rate near 70%, and across a set of novel drugs the majority of accessible animal efficacy studies appeared only after the first human trial, with a substantial fraction of drugs having no efficacy study published beforehand at all.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_08356a318e2577ab","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"laboratory-animal experiment publication rates; animal efficacy studies relative to human trials","model":"laboratory-animal experiment publication rates","outcome":"animal efficacy studies relative to human trials; non-publication and publication bias","method":"opinion survey vs protocol-to-publication tracking"}}
{"id":"clm_09da8ad4e9bbdd60","text":"The same instability appears at the assay level, where a machine-learning analysis pinned the test-condition variables driving divergent genotoxicity outcomes for most compounds, and in developmental studies where litter structure must be treated as the statistical unit or pooled control data will inflate apparent effects; laboratories increasingly run dedicated studies purely to generate source-specific historical databases where published incidences are lacking.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_09da8ad4e9bbdd60","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_09ef1fa4df987040","text":"The persistence of the data-welfare debt across FAIR data, virtual controls, and NAMs is not a technical accident but the predictable output of a reward structure that pays for publication counts and journal prestige while pricing stewardship at essentially zero — data-sharing appears in almost no promotion and tenure criteria, while peer-reviewed publications appear in nearly all, and researchers accordingly treat their data as a private asset whose release requires an incentive that does not exist.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_09ef1fa4df987040","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"academic reward structure and incentives","method":"promotion/tenure criteria and data-sharing behaviour"}}
{"id":"clm_0a358cc0f01a1db4","text":"Antibodies are worse still: more than 3.8 million \"research-grade\" antibodies are marketed with little validation against fewer than 500 highly validated clinical-grade reagents, so that inconsistent antibody performance is a first-order driver of irreproducibility that end-users must themselves control.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_0a358cc0f01a1db4","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0a63a766b7dcbc97","text":"That style is not neutrality for its own sake but a hedge against the false consensus a single, confidently repeated number can manufacture.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_0a63a766b7dcbc97","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"simulation-based reliability modeling","outcome":"epistemic hedging against false consensus","method":"meta-research on false findings; simulation-based reliability modeling"}}
{"id":"clm_0acc1dab3542368c","text":"On the benefit side, the incentive most often invoked — a citation advantage for open data — is real but modest and method-sensitive: a 122,000-publication analysis found that depositing data in a repository was associated with only a 4.3% citation advantage on average, and none for sharing code, whereas a synthetic-control study of a journal-level open-data mandate reported a much larger increase.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_0acc1dab3542368c","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0b4469f1840cce5f","text":"The specific operational instruments of data welfare are already being built under these banners: preclinical systematic reviews that establish whether existing animal data are strong enough to translate — and thereby justify or obviate new studies, living evidence summaries that continuously map what has already been shown so it need not be shown again, and pre-registration of review protocols to prevent unplanned duplication.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_0b4469f1840cce5f","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0cbecf4e4075f8b4","text":"The extreme range of a historical database is routinely used to argue that a marginal tumour increase is not adverse: a nano-titanium-dioxide inhalation study judged a bronchiolo-alveolar carcinoma increase non-adverse because it sat at the upper limit of the historical database, an expert glyphosate review discounted a significant high-dose increase because it fell within the historical range, and a re-analysis of vanadium pentoxide weakened a carcinogenicity signal to \"no evidence\" simply by adding twenty-five matched-diet studies that widened the historical range.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_0cbecf4e4075f8b4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0eaf1ecf5cc12376","text":"A cohort study of due trials on the EU register found only 49.5% posted results within the required window, with commercial sponsors far more compliant than non-commercial ones (68.1% versus 11.0%); a UK university audit found a mere 1.6% of due trials reported within a year; and mesenchymal-stromal-cell trials left over half of registry entries with no posted or published results at all.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_0eaf1ecf5cc12376","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"clinical trial results reporting","outcome":"clinical trial results reporting; research transparency / non-reporting","method":"registry reporting-compliance audit"}}
{"id":"clm_0f35419e6a0dfde9","text":"Asked about specific behaviours, 64% of ecologists and evolutionary biologists reported having failed to publish a non-significant result, 42% had collected more data after checking significance, and 51% had presented an unexpected finding as though predicted.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_0f35419e6a0dfde9","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_0fde28aeec8b0c15","text":"The empirical anchor the review returns to most often — that actual, usable data availability sits near two percent while declared availability and paperwork compliance sit far above it — recurs across FAIR audits, incentive studies, and governance evaluations alike, and it is against that near-static baseline — the empirical ~2% availability anchor — that every enforcement result must be judged.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_0fde28aeec8b0c15","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: overextended.","scope":{"population":"biomedical/animal research data; medical & health-sciences articles","model":"biomedical/animal research data; FAIR data & repositories","outcome":"medical & health-sciences articles; open-data mandates & governance","method":"data-availability audits; FAIR data & repositories"}}
{"id":"clm_108fdf63c743e111","text":"Reproducibility engineering is advancing too: bioprinted kidney organoids reached 93–99% viability across 96 wells with 1–4% deposition variability, and a standardised retinal-organoid protocol achieved 100% differentiation efficiency across lines that previously yielded 30–80%.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_108fdf63c743e111","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"bioprinted kidney organoids, retinal organoids","model":"bioprinted kidney organoids, retinal organoids","method":"bioprinting & standardised differentiation protocols"}}
{"id":"clm_109394cd4057a9c5","text":"A nationwide comparison found explicit 3Rs reporting increased from zero publications in 2009 to 3.2% in 2018.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_109394cd4057a9c5","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal research publications","model":"animal research publications","outcome":"explicit 3Rs reporting","method":"nationwide before-and-after reporting comparison"}}
{"id":"clm_109c0b6fb1673486","text":"Empirical moral psychology complicates the usual assumption that people reason as utilitarians about animals, finding instead weak deontological side-constraints that protect them far less than humans, and the recognition of sentience keeps expanding — to cephalopods on high-confidence evidence, even as the presumed non-sentience of other invertebrates is precisely what recommends them as lower-cost \"replacement\" organisms, a convenience the widening evidence base steadily undercuts, and, more broadly, driving a shift in the moral status accorded laboratory animals since the 1990s.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_109c0b6fb1673486","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_11dae37bc5a839eb","text":"The pattern is strikingly indifferent to therapeutic area: meta-analyses of neuroprotection in stroke, Parkinson's and Alzheimer's models, of sepsis and cardiomyopathy, of antidepressant and seizure paradigms, of stem-cell and exosome therapies for wounds, neuropathy and osteoarthritis, and even of zebrafish neurobehaviour all converge on the same reading — large, uniformly positive pooled effects resting on primary studies that failed to report the safeguards that would make those effects trustworthy.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_11dae37bc5a839eb","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal disease-model meta-analyses (many areas incl. zebrafish)","model":"animal disease-model meta-analyses (many areas incl. zebrafish)","outcome":"cross-domain low quality","method":"risk-of-bias reporting"}}
{"id":"clm_11e7c50e6784601f","text":"Optimistic syntheses describe a credibility revolution already delivering more negative results and higher-quality registered reports, yet the stagnation of statistical power over the same half-century warns against mistaking activity for improvement.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_11e7c50e6784601f","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"credibility revolution vs real improvement","method":"registered reports, negative results, power stagnation"}}
{"id":"clm_128edac99ed0fdb3","text":"A study of user-defined metadata in an electronic laboratory notebook found that many users made little effort to add metadata even when the facility existed, endangering their own ability to recover data later.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_128edac99ed0fdb3","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_12b4af9e800c6849","text":"Structural critiques argue oversight bodies lack the expertise and mandate to judge scientific merit at all, so their approval should not be read as evidence of adherence to anything beyond legal minima.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_12b4af9e800c6849","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_12e905ceb9b7b6cb","text":"The clinical stakes are concrete: of ten prescription drugs withdrawn from the United States market between 1997 and 2001, eight caused greater harm to women than to men, a record that motivated sex-disaggregated reporting standards.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_12e905ceb9b7b6cb","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_133331020e02653f","text":"A scoping review catalogued 17 harm-benefit decision resources and concluded that deliberation among members should be favoured over numeric scoring, yet cross-national analysis finds the harm-benefit cornerstone of the EU Directive deficiently transposed and inconsistently implemented.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_133331020e02653f","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"deliberation vs scoring; uneven implementation","method":"harm-benefit decision tools / EU transposition"}}
{"id":"clm_13c8dc85c2e607fd","text":"Interviews with data-sharing-platform stakeholders show the mechanism concretely: an evaluation system fixated on first and last authorship structurally undervalues the people who generate and curate data, so contributorship crediting is proposed as a corrective.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_13c8dc85c2e607fd","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"evaluation undervalues data generators; contributorship as a corrective","method":"authorship/contributorship credit systems"}}
{"id":"clm_15551c42677691e3","text":"Yet FAIRification remains young and unevenly implemented across health and toxicology data, the lack of harmonisation across assays, platforms, and analytical workflows is a named barrier to regulatory adoption, standardised documentation templates aligned to reporting guidance are only now being adopted by consortia, and building even one reusable knowledge base demanded heavy investment in governance, authorisation, and quality documentation.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_15551c42677691e3","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"FAIR implementation, harmonisation, documentation templates","outcome":"FAIRification young and uneven; a barrier to regulatory adoption","method":"assay/platform harmonisation; documentation standards (ToxTemp, GIVIMP); FAIR implementation, harmonisation, documentation templates"}}
{"id":"clm_1562d8a88cac4ff8","text":"The community response is qualification and quality-control criteria — coefficient-of-variation thresholds for organoid assays, donor-specific control thresholds for a vessel chip, and reproducibility-grading schemes for liver models — alongside consortium efforts to define contexts of use and even to build animal-tissue chips that could benchmark their human counterparts.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_1562d8a88cac4ff8","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"organoids, vessel chip, liver MPS","model":"organoids, vessel chip, liver MPS","outcome":"quality-control response to NAM variability","method":"CV/QC thresholds, qualification, contexts of use, animal-tissue benchmarking chips"}}
{"id":"clm_15e463f2b1c69823","text":"Formal sample-size calculation cut the required numbers in a radiation-countermeasure paradigm to less than half of typical usage, where historically hundreds of animals had been used with no power calculation at all; a refined pulmonary-embolism model reduced the mice needed per experiment by around 90% by measuring a specific biological response rather than a rare fatal endpoint; and incorporating historical control animals into the analysis reduced the number of concurrent controls needed by more than half without loss of power.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_15e463f2b1c69823","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_15f6b1f32a733ae9","text":"A retrospective study of nonrodent one-month studies went further, reporting that propensity-score-matched virtual controls yielded similar or higher sensitivity than concurrent controls to detect effects on body weight and clinical pathology when fold-change from baseline was used.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_15f6b1f32a733ae9","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_1601ec439f567b12","text":"The knowledge itself is compromised — the published animal record is filtered toward positive results, weakly protected against bias, and a poor, analysis-dependent predictor of human outcomes, with a direct six-intervention comparison showing benefit in animal models that vanished in patients and clinical success from first-in-human testing running at only single-digit-to-low-double-digit percentages.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_1601ec439f567b12","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal models (e.g. stroke); translation to patients / clinical success","model":"animal models (e.g. stroke)","outcome":"translation to patients / clinical success; compromised published animal record","method":"publication bias / predictive value"}}
{"id":"clm_169618b8b266cd6b","text":"Animal findings then translate to humans poorly and unpredictably: a direct six-intervention comparison showed benefit in animal head-injury models that evaporated in patients, a scoping review found published translational success spanning the entire range from none to complete, and independent analyses converge on a likelihood of moving from first-in-human testing to approval of only roughly 5–14%.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_169618b8b266cd6b","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal disease models; human trials and drug approval","model":"animal disease models","outcome":"human trials and drug approval; translational success/failure","method":"animal-to-human translation measurement"}}
{"id":"clm_17156774c21e167f","text":"When seventy-three independent teams analysed the same data to test the same hypothesis, their numerical results diverged so widely that most of the variance remained unexplained even after every analytic decision had been coded — a direct demonstration of how much latitude a reward for clean results can exploit.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_17156774c21e167f","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"reward for clean results can exploit analytic latitude","method":"analytic-flexibility variance across 73 teams on one dataset"}}
{"id":"clm_17967e1296ffbee0","text":"The link between competitive pressure and bias is nonetheless contested: although more productive environments produced more confirmatory results, a later cross-disciplinary meta-assessment found high-output, highly cited authors were not overall at greater risk of bias, locating inflation instead in small, early-career, and misconduct-prone work.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_17967e1296ffbee0","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"where bias inflation actually concentrates","method":"competition vs bias risk; small/early/highly-cited studies overestimate effects"}}
{"id":"clm_17a0c7b6bb718917","text":"The divergence appears cell-type driven, and it means that the same architectural upgrade can raise or lower apparent sensitivity depending on the biology underneath — a variability that only disciplined, comparable reporting can resolve.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_17a0c7b6bb718917","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"cell-type-dependent toxicity sensitivity (hepatic, cardiac iPSC models)","model":"cell-type-dependent toxicity sensitivity (hepatic, cardiac iPSC models); qAOP hierarchical calibration","outcome":"architecture-vs-biology variability requires disciplined reporting","method":"comparable reporting for NAM assays; qAOP hierarchical calibration"}}
{"id":"clm_189d21e33e050032","text":"Such models scale to hazard spaces that experiment cannot touch — candidate structures for a single chemical-warfare class can exceed 10,000 compounds, making in silico estimation of environmental fate the only feasible route.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_189d21e33e050032","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"in silico QSAR (environmental fate)","outcome":"hazard space exceeds experimental capacity","method":"in silico estimation for combinatorial chemical spaces; in silico QSAR (environmental fate)"}}
{"id":"clm_18c783635d59c0f2","text":"Reduction is visibly occurring — EU animal use fell 8.2% in a single year in safety pharmacology, and one otorhinolaryngology corpus recorded a 49.1% fall in animals used across two periods — but no study yet attributes such falls specifically to data reuse rather than to substitution, funding shifts, or reduced activity.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_18c783635d59c0f2","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal use","model":"animal use","outcome":"reduction occurring; causal link to data reuse unproven","method":"reporting audits of animal-use counts"}}
