{"id":"clm_2e0aea7bdf5c5fef","text":"Proposed remedies move from authorship toward structured contributorship, in which machine-readable role taxonomies record who curated data and ran code, though such schemes remain unevenly adopted and are undercut by promotion rules that simply count indexed publications.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_2e0aea7bdf5c5fef","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"machine-readable role taxonomies (CRediT/CRO)","outcome":"contributorship undercut by publication-counting promotion rules","method":"structured contributorship credit systems; machine-readable role taxonomies (CRediT/CRO)"}}
{"id":"clm_2f8f3944e4a574aa","text":"More broadly, reviews of predictive validity conclude that animal models are weak predictors of human drug safety and efficacy across therapeutic areas, a judgement borne out by case histories: Hedgehog-pathway inhibitors, once hoped to treat a quarter of human cancers, responded clinically in only two rare tumour types; of 101 highly promising basic-science findings, only five reached licensed clinical use two decades later; creatine, neuroprotective in Parkinson's models, showed no benefit in trials of nearly 2,000 patients; and umbilical-cord-blood therapy, significant across preclinical lung-injury outcomes, produced no reduction in the corresponding clinical endpoint.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_2f8f3944e4a574aa","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
