{"id":"clm_312a3899b0fe5dda","text":"The clinical cousin of the virtual control — the external control arm — already features in a meaningful share of oncology approvals, which suggests the preclinical acceptance gap is a matter of validation and precedent rather than of principle.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_312a3899b0fe5dda","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"preclinical VCG acceptance; oncology regulatory approvals (external control arm)","model":"preclinical VCG acceptance; external/virtual control arms","outcome":"oncology regulatory approvals (external control arm); the acceptance gap","method":"validation and precedent vs principle; external/virtual control arms"}}
{"id":"clm_31c2d4e620cc2599","text":"Third, and most consequential, it is unproven that evaluation reform changes behaviour rather than metrics: the reform manifesto and the natural-selection model make opposite predictions, and a scoping review found that of more than a hundred studies of reproducibility interventions only a handful measured reproducibility itself rather than a presumed proxy.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_31c2d4e620cc2599","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"behaviour vs metrics; reform vs natural selection","method":"evaluation reform; reproducibility measurement; proxy outcomes"}}
{"id":"clm_324cbbf1d6089244","text":"An expert workshop assessment counters that these systems have neither been widely adopted by the pharmaceutical industry nor reached regulated drug-authorisation processes at all.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_324cbbf1d6089244","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"regulated drug-authorisation","outcome":"regulated drug-authorisation; industry/regulatory adoption of MPS","method":"MPS / organ-on-chip"}}
{"id":"clm_327663af60a4d5cf","text":"Fourth, ethical review must be given the expertise and mandate to treat scientific quality — and the reuse of prior data that would avoid repeating an experiment — as part of the harm-benefit judgment rather than as someone else's problem.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_327663af60a4d5cf","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"ethical review should assess scientific quality","method":"harm-benefit judgment / data reuse in ethics review"}}
{"id":"clm_340b82705318d705","text":"The most frequently repeated single figure — that more than half of preclinical research is irreproducible, at a cost of tens of billions of dollars a year in the United States alone — is influential but rests on a modelled economic estimate whose provenance is not fully transparent, and it is best read as an order-of-magnitude claim rather than a measurement.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_340b82705318d705","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: suggestive; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"preclinical life-science research reproducibility","model":"preclinical life-science research reproducibility","outcome":"the 50%/$28B figure is an order-of-magnitude estimate, not a measurement","method":"economic modelling of irreproducibility cost"}}
{"id":"clm_3496fd5d30b1dc1d","text":"A 2023 independent reimplementation replicated most model results and identified a coding error affecting the replication-rate dynamics, but reported that the original conclusion was unchanged.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_3496fd5d30b1dc1d","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"independent reimplementation of the natural-selection-of-bad-science model","outcome":"replication result and coding-error caveat","method":"agent-based simulation replication; independent reimplementation of the natural-selection-of-bad-science model"}}
{"id":"clm_34a0d91aef052ddb","text":"A high-content three-dimensional hepatocyte-spheroid assay detected 36 of 42 known hepatotoxins with no false positives among safe compounds, and a functional variant-classification assay integrated with in silico prediction correctly classified 87% of Lynch-syndrome variants.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_34a0d91aef052ddb","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"iPSC hepatocyte 3D spheroids; MMR variant function; Lynch-syndrome variant classification","model":"iPSC hepatocyte 3D spheroids; MMR variant function; in silico pathogenicity integration","outcome":"Lynch-syndrome variant classification; NAM predictive performance","method":"high-content 3D assay; functional variant classification; in silico pathogenicity integration"}}
{"id":"clm_34a6bd26e9917641","text":"The successor projects assembling standardised control databases name regulatory acceptance as their explicit goal precisely because it has not yet been secured.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_34a6bd26e9917641","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"nonclinical toxicology control-animal databases","model":"nonclinical toxicology control-animal databases","outcome":"regulatory acceptance not yet secured","method":"VCG database assembly for regulatory acceptance"}}
{"id":"clm_34ffa80b7b2e04b5","text":"A transparency audit of studies using animal models of opioid addiction found near-total absence of open-science practices: none preregistered, none sharing analytical code, raw data accessible for only about three percent, and the great majority lacking any sample-size justification.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_34ffa80b7b2e04b5","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal models of opioid addiction","model":"animal models of opioid addiction; analytical-code sharing","outcome":"near-total absence of open-science practices","method":"transparency/open-science audit (preregistration, sample-size justification); analytical-code sharing"}}
{"id":"clm_356d764ddbbb85c5","text":"One position holds that \"it is not sustainable to keep accumulating and maintaining all datasets for rapid access, considering the monetary and ecological cost of maintaining repositories\".","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_356d764ddbbb85c5","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_35ac85942839e5c1","text":"Older and modeled estimates sit in the same range or below it — one in 33 compounds in castration-resistant prostate cancer, an overall clinical success rate near 12% falling to 4% for Alzheimer's-type indications, and 14–32% for antibody therapeutics — and the roughly 90% attrition rate, attributed in part to species differences, is now cited as a rationale for the FDA Modernization Act 2.0's opening to non-animal methods.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_35ac85942839e5c1","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_35ccc8ba9e2c1cd7","text":"A data-generating group presented the same class of battery as a promising approach already usable for neurodevelopmental hazard assessment and prioritisation, while noting its rankings diverged from high-throughput screening.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_35ccc8ba9e2c1cd7","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"human cell-based DNT in vitro battery","model":"human cell-based DNT in vitro battery","outcome":"readiness of DNT IVB","method":"DNT IVB hazard assessment / prioritisation"}}
{"id":"clm_36c524e2db9e7d20","text":"First, it remains unproven that FAIRification causally increases reuse rather than merely raising nominal availability: optimistic reviews and pessimistic retrieval audits disagree, and even the direction of the effect is uncertain because automated FAIRification can inject the very deficiencies it is meant to cure.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_36c524e2db9e7d20","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: uncertain; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"rare-disease EHR data","model":"FAIRification and data reuse","outcome":"rare-disease EHR data; availability vs reuse causality","method":"causal evaluation of FAIR; automated FAIRification; FAIRification and data reuse"}}
{"id":"clm_36f4f709513c90c4","text":"A checklist that a journal implements and checks has been associated with more complete reporting, though even a requirement enforced at the revision stage lifted full compliance with core bias-reduction items only into a minority of papers, whereas the mere publication of reporting guidelines left adherence unchanged or even lower, and protocol registration and data access stayed almost entirely unreported long after they became best practice.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_36f4f709513c90c4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3724a884285141aa","text":"Review-level syntheses hold that \"FAIR data leads to improved data sharing in different scientific domains\", treating the principles as a demonstrated remedy.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_3724a884285141aa","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3727c094cb228e45","text":"On acute severity, the standard instrument fares no better unaided: in a rat liver-cirrhosis surgery model the usual welfare score-sheet parameters were insufficient to predict death until the cut-offs were retrospectively re-optimised, whereas an evidence-based behavioural and biochemical analysis of electrical kindling concluded that a simple welfare measure was a valid basis for grading severity.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_3727c094cb228e45","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3864499518574c63","text":"A second limitation is conceptual: the data-welfare construct is load-bearing only where lost data could genuinely have been banked and reused, and merely rhetorical where reuse was impossible in principle; treating every unshared file as literally equivalent to animal suffering would trivialise the physical harms the 3Rs were built to address, and the honest version of the argument concedes this boundary.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_3864499518574c63","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal welfare / physical harms","model":"animal welfare / physical harms; data banking and reuse","outcome":"boundary of the data-welfare construct","method":"reuse feasibility; data banking and reuse"}}
{"id":"clm_38c1a5e3a3bb0928","text":"It is unresolved, and the disagreement tracks the vantage point — panel review versus method developer.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_38c1a5e3a3bb0928","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"vantage-point-dependent readiness assessment","method":"DNT in vitro methods"}}
{"id":"clm_38cce2afcea6e857","text":"A systematic audit of omics studies in the Gene Expression Omnibus found that only 11.5% shared all of their important phenotype metadata while 37.9% shared less than 40%, with roughly a quarter of critical metadata omitted on average.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_38cce2afcea6e857","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_39bba55bc0b1dafe","text":"Open-practice badges at one journal — an enforced, visible signal — raised reported open data from under 3% to 39% within about eighteen months while comparison journals did not move; a mandatory data-and-code policy checked at review pushed provision to 96.5% of manuscripts; and automated screening tools that score rigor at scale confirm that combining checks catches items that peer review misses, because reviewers demonstrably do not enforce guidelines on their own.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_39bba55bc0b1dafe","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"automated rigor-screening tools","outcome":"enforcement efficacy (partly transferred from psychology/ecology)","method":"badges, mandates, automated checks; automated rigor-screening tools"}}
{"id":"clm_3a304347c8059b41","text":"Husbandry variables normally treated as invisible turn out to move results: the time of day a microbiome sample is taken can change a study's conclusion more than the intervention does, something as basic as body temperature shifts stroke infarct size by dozens of percent, and bedding material, chow diet, and cage-level gut-flora heterogeneity each perturb metabolic and cancer models.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_3a304347c8059b41","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3a81c58c85a6c751","text":"When the ICMJE made prospective registration a condition of publication in 2004, annual registrations rose from 3,294 to 23,384 within a decade — a fivefold jump relative to publication growth.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_3a81c58c85a6c751","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"clinical trial registration","outcome":"clinical trial registration; transparency policy effect","method":"prospective trial registration mandate"}}
{"id":"clm_3a8449cd97a40d91","text":"Yet adoption is concentrated in regulatory oncology and rare-disease settings and remains vanishingly rare elsewhere: only seven of 1,115 open-label extension studies over a decade used an external control, and an earlier review found only about 8% of oncology approvals used real-world evidence for efficacy, all retrospectively.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_3a8449cd97a40d91","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"open-label extension studies; FDA oncology approvals","outcome":"open-label extension studies; FDA oncology approvals; adoption concentrated in oncology/rare disease","method":"external-control / RWE adoption"}}
{"id":"clm_3b13d89bfb966d91","text":"The survey underpinning the ARRIVE guidelines found that only 59% of 271 animal papers stated their hypothesis and basic animal characteristics, while 87% did not report randomisation and 86% did not report blinding; a decade later, adherence remained inconsistent enough to prompt a slimmed-down \"Essential 10\", and a randomised controlled trial at a major journal showed that simply requesting a completed checklist at submission produced no manuscript that met every ARRIVE item.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_3b13d89bfb966d91","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal-research publications","model":"animal-research publications","outcome":"reporting-guideline efficacy","method":"ARRIVE reporting & checklist RCT"}}
{"id":"clm_3b3be88fb8d83910","text":"The opposing camp holds the tool is retainable if improved: the discourse and metric models are not mutually exclusive and can be combined, and validated welfare-scoring can supply the missing quantitative side.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_3b3be88fb8d83910","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3ce37b95888d033c","text":"Open-access publishing has grown strongly under funder and repository mandates — top-performing universities reached 80–90% open access by 2017 — yet that reach is starkly uneven: over 60% of Tunisian publications remain paywalled behind unaffordable article-processing charges, and preregistration and data-sharing practices in PhD theses rose only modestly and were unaffected by how established a department's open-science culture was.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_3ce37b95888d033c","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"uneven reach of open-science policies","method":"OA / preregistration / data-sharing uptake"}}
{"id":"clm_3ce927e4e5c6b3a1","text":"Industry reviews describe VCGs, second-species requirements and information sharing as currently \"under scrutiny,\" with companies and regulators reluctant to abandon existing paradigms until replacement approaches are validated and globally accepted, and the Japanese analysis catalogues five concrete obstacles because current guidelines still mandate concurrent controls for pivotal studies.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_3ce927e4e5c6b3a1","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"nonclinical toxicology animal studies","model":"nonclinical toxicology animal studies","outcome":"regulatory scrutiny and obstacles to VCG adoption","method":"VCG, second-species, concurrent-control requirements"}}
{"id":"clm_3d0ae93ea9b6a102","text":"An industry working group built a culture-of-care framework but cautioned it must not be used as an auditing or benchmarking instrument, only as a starting point for reflection within each establishment's constraints, lest it degrade into a tick-box exercise.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_3d0ae93ea9b6a102","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3d0e46ddb0d7bba4","text":"Donor-to-donor variability drives a liver-chip's urea-production coefficient of variation from under 5% on day 1 to 20% by day 7; an independent robustness study of a commercial liver microphysiological system found stable function to 17 days but appreciable within- and between-study variability; organoids exhibit necrotic cores and considerable variability from one preparation to the next; standard viability assays give inaccurate readouts in three-dimensional constructs; and the zebrafish developmental-toxicity protocol varies between laboratories, producing discordant data for identical compounds.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_3d0e46ddb0d7bba4","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"liver-chip, organoids, zebrafish embryo","model":"liver-chip, organoids, zebrafish embryo","outcome":"reproducibility/variability of NAMs","method":"MPS reproducibility, 3D viability assays, ZEDTA"}}
{"id":"clm_3d63bd98975b6b39","text":"A group-sequential device trial that borrowed from four heterogeneous historical control studies enrolled roughly 1,497 rather than 2,386 patients under scenarios where the historical and current data were congruent — about a 37% enrolment reduction — while holding Type I error and power at nominal levels, despite substantial between-study heterogeneity in the borrowed data (I2 of 92%).","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_3d63bd98975b6b39","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3d9961bbe18af6a9","text":"A subtler foundational gap runs through the whole edifice: the 3Rs rest on a welfarist premise, inherited from their intellectual patrons, that a painless death is not a harm, so animal death is largely omitted from 3Rs-based regulation even though it is the modal outcome of a research life.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_3d9961bbe18af6a9","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_3db203ac409ad955","text":"The stewardship failure recurs across FAIR data, virtual controls, and non-animal methods not because each field is separately deficient but because they answer to the same reward structure — one that pays for publication counts and journal prestige while pricing data stewardship at essentially zero and treating a researcher's data as a private asset with no release incentive.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_3db203ac409ad955","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"data sharing (FAIR)","outcome":"reward structure / political economy","method":"RPT criteria and stewardship incentives; data sharing (FAIR)"}}
{"id":"clm_3ea05f76f598ec8f","text":"Governance offers the enforced alternative, and here the evidence is clearer: a checklist mandated and checked at revision moved reporting where the same checklist merely requested at submission did not, and open-practice signals that are verified deliver usable data where unenforced mandates do not.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_3ea05f76f598ec8f","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal-research reporting (ARRIVE/Landis)","model":"animal-research reporting (ARRIVE/Landis)","outcome":"governance and enforcement vs voluntary compliance","method":"checklist enforcement at revision vs submission; verified open-practice signals"}}
{"id":"clm_3ea93f22403f5abd","text":"Regulatory-facing NAM programmes report the same bounded successes — teratogenicity assays predicting 75 known teratogens with 73–82% predictivity, rising to 88% when platforms are combined; zebrafish-embryo exposure correlating with mammalian and human values for reference developmental toxicants; and validated QSAR/read-across meeting OECD thresholds for pesticide developmental-toxicity prioritisation.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_3ea93f22403f5abd","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"zebrafish embryo / stem-cell teratogenicity models","model":"zebrafish embryo / stem-cell teratogenicity models; QSAR / q-RASAR","outcome":"NAM predictivity meeting regulatory thresholds","method":"developmental-toxicity NAM validation; QSAR / q-RASAR"}}
{"id":"clm_3f90d23d148d2775","text":"Second, the target must be actual, FAIR-compliant availability and reuse, not declared availability, since the two differ by an order of magnitude and reform that clears only the lower bar changes nothing downstream.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_3f90d23d148d2775","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"medical data availability","model":"data reuse / FAIR compliance","outcome":"medical data availability; reform must target actual availability","method":"declared vs actual data sharing; data reuse / FAIR compliance"}}
{"id":"clm_40ae00e5f511f91d","text":"The templated ISA-model alternative generates structured metadata in parallel at each level of a project so that submission is guided rather than optional.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_40ae00e5f511f91d","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_4226fdd142acb1ca","text":"Yet an archive built on an enforced community standard documents more than 150 reuse publications.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_4226fdd142acb1ca","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_43039aafb7f506d1","text":"The pattern is not confined to stroke: across 4,445 datasets in 160 meta-analyses of six neurological conditions, the observed number of \"positive\" studies (1,719) vastly exceeded the number predicted by their statistical power (919), and only eight of the 160 meta-analyses were free of any excess-significance or small-study signal.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_43039aafb7f506d1","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal neurological-disease models","model":"animal neurological-disease models","outcome":"publication bias","method":"excess-significance test"}}
{"id":"clm_4310d1e89bf6a644","text":"A manual openness/FAIR audit of 555 bioscience papers at one university found the fraction sharing all relevant data rose from 7% in 2014 to 45% in 2023.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_4310d1e89bf6a644","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"bioscience research","model":"bioscience research","outcome":"data-sharing improvement","method":"openness/FAIR institutional audit"}}
{"id":"clm_43c3076be58b9523","text":"Philosophical reviews argue that although theories of moral status rest on incompatible foundations, their practical implications for research converge more than expected; others challenge the graded view directly, criticising the justifications for assigning lower status to less cognitively complex animals and the assumption that they suffer less, or defend sentience as the necessary and sufficient criterion against the objection that we cannot know which beings possess it.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_43c3076be58b9523","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_44f5be0d61757bdc","text":"That figure has been restated by the group that produced it and folded into wider estimates ranging from US\\$28 billion nationally to over US\\$200 billion worldwide.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_44f5be0d61757bdc","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"US & worldwide preclinical research","model":"US & worldwide preclinical research; economic estimates","outcome":"research-waste cost","method":"economic estimates"}}
{"id":"clm_461ca3d3febdb2d9","text":"The through-line connects the human and animal costs: euthanising surplus animals and being unable to alleviate distress are among the strongest job-specific stressors reported, in a workforce where nearly everyone has performed euthanasia and where the strain is attributed to institutional culture more than to the animal work itself, so a system that breeds and kills animals to regenerate data it already produced imposes a double harm — on the animals wasted and on the people who must waste them.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_461ca3d3febdb2d9","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_46b4bb20d8658e2c","text":"Where the underlying models can be audited, the shortfall is quantitative rather than rhetorical: a systematic assessment of 178 in silico thyroid-disruption models found only about 18% fully compliant with the OECD assessment framework, the adverse outcome pathways that anchor mechanistic NAMs are largely immature — most cardiotoxicity-network pathways remain under development or unevaluated — and validating a method by concordance with animal data is itself a weak anchor because many animal tests were never validated for human relevance.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_46b4bb20d8658e2c","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"in silico thyroid-disruption / QSAR models","outcome":"maturity of mechanistic NAM anchors","method":"OECD assessment framework, AOPs, animal-concordance validation; in silico thyroid-disruption / QSAR models"}}
{"id":"clm_46c2d4ea5c825809","text":"Abstract principles were translated into quantifiable metrics implemented in open-source assessment tools such as F-UJI; maturity models and crosswalks now let a repository score its own compliance across dimensions, and one such crosswalk of three established approaches found strong correlations in the discovery and accessibility dimensions.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_46c2d4ea5c825809","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_473403c4d01c6552","text":"In a landmark demonstration, inbred mouse strains tested simultaneously in three laboratories under rigorously equated apparatus and protocols still differed systematically in behaviour across sites; a single retest of a P<0.05 behavioural result reproduces only about 60% of the time; behavioural measures carry coefficients of variation two to three times those of clinical chemistry; and inbred strains accumulate genetic drift that changes their phenotype over time and place, compounded by strain-background effects on stem-cell and xenograft phenotype.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_473403c4d01c6552","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_4745ec499105777c","text":"Independent audits from unrelated corners reinforce the low ceiling: only 4.5% of articles at a journal with a strong data-sharing policy actually shared data; the Reproducibility Project: Cancer Biology could obtain the data needed to compute effect sizes for just 4 of 193 experiments; and even where 68.6% of trials declared data sharing after an editorial mandate, actual practice diverged sharply by funder.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_4745ec499105777c","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"preclinical cancer biology; clinical trials","model":"preclinical cancer biology","outcome":"clinical trials; declared vs actual sharing","method":"data-sharing audits"}}
{"id":"clm_475ab2267385a171","text":"Selective and distorted reporting compounds at the analysis stage too: post-randomisation attrition can induce selection bias even under a null effect, pandemic-era meta-analyses showed 70.6% reporting-conduct discrepancies, and sex-difference claims are frequently asserted without a supporting statistical test even as policies push sex inclusion — while in some fields most animal studies still use male animals only.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_475ab2267385a171","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal studies (sex bias, attrition); meta-analysis reporting","model":"animal studies (sex bias, attrition)","outcome":"meta-analysis reporting; selective and distorted reporting","method":"analysis-stage bias / sex-based analysis"}}
{"id":"clm_483c1f66c162c4c9","text":"A survey of 118 palaeontological and Earth-science databases found that roughly 85% of community-curated databases have lifespans under fifteen years, with peaks in database loss tracking five-year funding cycles — decades of volunteered data at risk of disappearing.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_483c1f66c162c4c9","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
