{"id":"clm_4b335dbddef594b7","text":"Open practices are moreover associated with tangible career returns — more citations, attention, and opportunities — a citation advantage that is real but inconsistent across studies for open access, clearer in single-field analyses, and more robust — roughly nine percent more citations — for open data, while a compulsory open-data mandate causally raised a journal's citations.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_4b335dbddef594b7","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"OA citation effects in medical-education and orthopaedic literatures","outcome":"OA citation effects in medical-education and orthopaedic literatures; open practices yield career returns","method":"OA vs open-data citation advantage; mandate effect"}}
{"id":"clm_4b3429eb6be95b94","text":"Exchange standards leak as badly as models: in one single-institution study, biomarker data present in the source record were missing in 80–100% of downstream standardized extracts.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_4b3429eb6be95b94","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_4b82eeac8b5eda14","text":"Pulmonary-hypertension and dairy-cattle trial reviews reach the same conclusion, and translational assessments note that ARRIVE and PREPARE have been introduced but seldom implemented, with progress on external validity virtually absent.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_4b82eeac8b5eda14","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal disease models (PAH, dairy cattle)","model":"animal disease models (PAH, dairy cattle)","outcome":"external validity","method":"ARRIVE/PREPARE implementation"}}
{"id":"clm_4d555f79a91d3009","text":"Risk-of-bias tooling has become standard in preclinical evidence synthesis — SYRCLE and CAMARADES now appear routinely — yet the scores they return hover in the middling range and reporting of construct validity is essentially absent.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_4d555f79a91d3009","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal disease models","model":"animal disease models","outcome":"absence of construct-validity reporting","method":"SYRCLE / CAMARADES risk-of-bias"}}
{"id":"clm_4e314a8ce603a41e","text":"A survey of European mouse and primate papers two decades apart found no increase over twenty years in reported 3Rs implementation, with mouse papers averaging zero of ten possible items; a fourteen-year survey of nearly 3,800 preclinical urology studies found sample-size estimation reported in 1.0% of them; a systematic review of degradable-metal bone studies found adherence to the ARRIVE 2.0 essentials at 42% with protocol registration and data access almost never reported; and the depression-model literature combined intermediate reporting quality with a 2.35% data-sharing response rate.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_4e314a8ce603a41e","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_4f14f523e998bdbf","text":"Electronic laboratory notebooks are advocated across chemistry, computational drug discovery, and regulated bioanalysis as the route from analogue records to FAIR-aligned capture at source, and structured, template-driven capture demonstrably helps — an AI-assisted chemistry notebook with built-in structured documentation improved student adherence to good data practice, and ontology-based notebooks can capture and automatically validate complex instrument metadata that would otherwise be lost.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_4f14f523e998bdbf","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_4f6073513385becf","text":"In a direct comparison of six interventions with unambiguous clinical evidence, corticosteroids benefited animal head-injury models (pooled odds ratio 0.58) yet showed no benefit in patients, and a scoping review of 121 quantitative animal-to-human comparisons found published translational success rates spanning the entire range from 0% to 100%, with animal-human toxicity concordance of 71% across species but only 43% for rodents alone.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_4f6073513385becf","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_52a63184b4d674ef","text":"framed this as a political economy in which non-sharing, selective reporting, and — at the margin — outright fabrication are individually rational responses to the system that rewards them, so that questionable practices are widely admitted and fraud-enabling operations are growing faster than legitimate science.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_52a63184b4d674ef","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"political economy of incentives and fraud","method":"QRPs, selective reporting, non-sharing"}}
{"id":"clm_52ee3b131b8613a4","text":"Reviews frame that weighing as, at best, a way to align welfare with scientific value — arguing that reduction and refinement can act in synergy with better science rather than against it — and set out the deliberative and metric models available for performing it.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_52ee3b131b8613a4","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_5310fe1bd7d7a409","text":"Two systematic reviews of reviews, twenty-one years apart in coverage, found that 86.0% and then 87.9% of the studies they examined reported suboptimal adherence to reporting guidelines despite those guidelines' wide availability.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_5310fe1bd7d7a409","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"health-care research reporting","outcome":"health-care research reporting; availability vs adherence","method":"reporting-guideline adherence"}}
{"id":"clm_536931fcfee707da","text":"Virtual control groups interrupt the loop at the most concrete point available, reusing curated control-animal data so that a group of animals never enters the next study; found a stable Reduction estimate of roughly a quarter of control animals and an infrastructure that already exists at scale, but a dividend conditional on endpoint-specific concordance and still unaccepted by any regulator for a pivotal preclinical study.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_536931fcfee707da","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"regulatory toxicity studies (rodents, Wistar rat)","model":"regulatory toxicity studies (rodents, Wistar rat); virtual control groups from historical control data","outcome":"regulatory acceptance of reuse","method":"VCG-CCG concordance and Reduction; virtual control groups from historical control data"}}
{"id":"clm_53ef7b2a710e86fa","text":"Proponents assert that non-animal methods are, in certain settings, already appropriate for assuring chemical-ingredient safety, with only regulatory adoption lagging.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_53ef7b2a710e86fa","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"regulatory readiness of NAMs (proponent view)","method":"NAMs / NGRA for chemical ingredients"}}
{"id":"clm_553bfa1b646e40d6","text":"The structural reasons are specific: US committees are not required to hold subject-matter or replacement-methods expertise, are not required to verify that a study is non-duplicative, and mostly approve through single-member review, so their approval should not be read as evidence of ethical adherence beyond legal minimums.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_553bfa1b646e40d6","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"approval does not warrant ethical adherence","method":"US IACUC review process"}}
{"id":"clm_5580ba286d4abf1a","text":"Pooling control clinical-chemistry across five companies revealed systematic per-company offsets from the combined mean, and background lesion rates depend heavily on study duration — spontaneous liver necrosis in control rats rose from about 2% at ages matching one-month studies to about 8% at six-month terminal-sacrifice ages.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_5580ba286d4abf1a","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_5591e45f4d3361a4","text":"On the regulatory side, the FDA CDER repository of studies submitted in the SEND standard grew from more than 1,800 studies queried in 2020 to over 10,000 datasets a few years later, and individual corporate databases have supported meta-analyses aggregating tens of thousands of animals — one spanning 24,358 animals and more than 232,000 histological observations across hundreds of studies.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_5591e45f4d3361a4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_55a7e8db1827f197","text":"In a multi-company Han Wistar rat database, study year was the most influential factor among body-weight class, company, and year, with medium mean effect sizes of 0.127 in females and 0.117 in males.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_55a7e8db1827f197","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"Han Wistar rat control data","model":"Han Wistar rat control data; multi-company virtual-control-group database","outcome":"temporal drift in historical control data","method":"covariate effect-size analysis; multi-company virtual-control-group database"}}
{"id":"clm_55e98f414da87a05","text":"That reproducibility is contingent on power and design, rather than a fixed property of a field, is underscored by genetics: genome-wide significant variants replicated 85% of the time in well-powered biobank data — but only 58% for binary versus 95% for quantitative traits — whereas the earlier, underpowered candidate-gene era found robust replication persistently elusive.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_55e98f414da87a05","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_56206a7ab9de8222","text":"In skin sensitisation, defined approaches integrating multiple non-animal methods underpin the first OECD guideline of its kind, presented as performing equivalently to or better than animal tests, and a proof-of-concept extension to agrochemical mixtures achieved 85.0% sensitivity.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_56206a7ab9de8222","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"skin sensitisation (human-relevant in vitro / in chemico)","model":"skin sensitisation (human-relevant in vitro / in chemico); in silico components of defined approaches","outcome":"NAM equivalence to animal tests","method":"OECD Guideline 497 defined approaches; in silico components of defined approaches"}}
{"id":"clm_5621811cc329d68c","text":"The middle ground is empirical and sobering: an expert workshop concluded that despite academic enthusiasm, microphysiological systems have not been widely adopted by industry nor reached regulated authorisation, with assay qualification and a stakeholder communication gap the major barriers, and mapping reviews of organ-on-chip stress that clear evidence standards for when a model may replace animals are still lacking.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_5621811cc329d68c","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
