{"id":"clm_586438c37d91b132","text":"An observational study of a checklist that Nature journals instead mandated at revision found that the proportion of in vivo papers meeting all four \"Landis\" bias-reduction criteria rose from 0% to 16.4%, with no change in matched control journals.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_586438c37d91b132","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"in vivo animal research","model":"in vivo animal research","outcome":"enforcement efficacy","method":"checklist mandated at revision"}}
{"id":"clm_58a76bd2cdf3c864","text":"The opposing position holds that animal models remain essential for understanding complex disease pathogenesis and progression.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_58a76bd2cdf3c864","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_59da77f356da88f0","text":"The persistent obstacle is as much commercial as technical: the single biggest barrier to building shared preclinical safety databases has been the unwillingness of sponsors to share proprietary data, and even with the data assembled, reuse has intrinsic analytical limits — a likelihood-ratio analysis of the same eTOX database found inter-species histopathological concordance to be rare.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_59da77f356da88f0","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_59fcf8eb1e5ff095","text":"A probability-bounds economic model combining published irreproducibility estimates with United States life-science spending puts the cumulative preclinical irreproducibility rate at a midpoint of 53.3%, implying roughly US\\$28 billion per year of non-reproducible preclinical research in the United States alone.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_59fcf8eb1e5ff095","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: suggestive; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"US preclinical life-science research","model":"US preclinical life-science research; economic modeling","outcome":"cost of irreproducibility","method":"probability-bounds estimation; economic modeling"}}
{"id":"clm_5a196c5559228836","text":"An analysis of Gene Ontology molecular-function annotations estimated that 64% of UniProtKB proteins are incompletely annotated and that inconsistencies affect 83% of protein functions and at least 23% of proteins; most annotations are generated by automated electronic inference rather than expert curation, so the bulk of the record is broad and not experimentally verified; a single co-annotation quality-control system corrected over 380,000 inferred annotations traced to just 54 mapping errors; and even the curated reference plant genome had experimental or predicted localization for only 90% of the proteome in its best-covered aspect.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_5a196c5559228836","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_5aaea8da42c47adb","text":"The first is FAIR data — data that are Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable — the near-universal standard for good stewardship and the subject of.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_5aaea8da42c47adb","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: definition; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"FAIR data principles","outcome":"data-stewardship standard","method":"research data management; FAIR data principles"}}
{"id":"clm_5c15fa31f0344f82","text":"Set against these encouraging results is the clinical-pathology finding that when concurrent controls were replaced with virtual ones in three legacy studies, 31%, 40% and 49% of quantitative parameters became statistically non-reproducible.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_5c15fa31f0344f82","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_5dab01aff63377ad","text":"Uptake surveys in animal-adjacent fields find the same low floor: only 21% of applied-ethology researchers were even aware of FAIR principles and 9% had preregistered; 39.2% of Swiss animal-study directors had never heard of preregistration; and preregistration of animal and in vitro protocols remains marginal in absolute numbers despite functioning registries.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_5dab01aff63377ad","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal and in vitro research","model":"animal and in vitro research","outcome":"low awareness / uptake floor","method":"FAIR / preregistration uptake surveys and registries"}}
{"id":"clm_5e082a4339742007","text":"A multi-company clinical-pathology analysis reached the opposite emphasis, finding study year the most influential covariate of all on control laboratory values.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_5e082a4339742007","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_5fd58a919e2434dc","text":"The 3Rs literature raises a parallel worry that oversight has become procedural rather than substantive.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_5fd58a919e2434dc","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: suggestive; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal-research oversight","model":"animal-research oversight","outcome":"procedural vs substantive oversight","method":"3Rs framework"}}
{"id":"clm_60a29fbf01814534","text":"Naming this loop is the review's central conceptual contribution, because it converts an abstract data-management concern into a specific, actionable claim about the 3Rs, and it locates the harm precisely where the field is least inclined to look — in the byte that is discarded rather than the procedure that is performed.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_60a29fbf01814534","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: definition; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"preclinical animal welfare","model":"preclinical animal welfare","outcome":"the discarded-byte loop as located harm","method":"data sharing and the 3Rs"}}
{"id":"clm_615b2ee1da50b2d3","text":"The kinetic layer that converts an in vitro concentration into a human dose is itself only moderately accurate: a generic high-throughput physiologically based model predicted peak plasma concentration within tenfold of in vivo values for only half of chemicals and within threefold for 31%, with a systematic lipophilicity-dependent bias.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_615b2ee1da50b2d3","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"generic high-throughput PBK model","outcome":"kinetic-layer accuracy","method":"IVIVE dose extrapolation; generic high-throughput PBK model"}}
