{"id":"clm_63e08fde8ce016d8","text":"One of the most consequential applications is paediatric extrapolation, where adult data are borrowed to make otherwise infeasible child trials analysable, and clinical methods that shrink the required control-group size while preserving frequentist operating characteristics are the direct statistical analogue of the preclinical virtual control group.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_63e08fde8ce016d8","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"pediatric drug trials (adult-to-child extrapolation)","outcome":"pediatric drug trials (adult-to-child extrapolation); clinical analogue of preclinical VCG","method":"dynamic borrowing shrinking control size with frequentist control"}}
{"id":"clm_6405dab755531d78","text":"Researcher and resource identifiers are similarly patchy — ORCID coverage differs substantially between institutions and data sources, and is not yet sufficient for automated reporting — with the consequence that data reuse cannot even be detected: applying a link-resolution framework to one university's outputs raised the availability of author names on dataset links from 2.4% to 89.2%, and only then could a handful of reuse cases be identified at all.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_6405dab755531d78","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
