{"id":"clm_7a9c25a1f059fce8","text":"A former oversight-committee chair argues that applying harm–benefit analysis to individual projects induces a systematic bias against basic research and can increase net harm, and should be replaced by two independent principles — societal benefit and minimal justified harm.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_7a9c25a1f059fce8","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7acdd13b4115701a","text":"Even mandates do not close the gap, because they raise nominal accessibility without raising quality: an audit of ecology and evolution datasets archived under strong public-archiving policies found most incomplete or unusable for reuse.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_7acdd13b4115701a","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"archived dataset completeness/reusability","outcome":"mandates raise nominal accessibility, not quality","method":"public-archiving mandate audit; archived dataset completeness/reusability"}}
{"id":"clm_7bdc125507284454","text":"One rationale for standardisation is that reducing genetic variability can reduce the number of animals required.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_7bdc125507284454","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"inbred experimental animals","model":"inbred experimental animals","outcome":"Reduction rationale","method":"sample-size rationale for reducing genetic variability"}}
{"id":"clm_7bde574d0eb27cc6","text":"An expert panel concluded that the human developmental-neurotoxicity in vitro battery may serve for initial screening but is not yet a complete or surrogate approach for classifying a chemical as a human developmental neurotoxicant, and needs further validation.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_7bde574d0eb27cc6","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"human DNT in vitro battery","model":"human DNT in vitro battery","outcome":"regulatory readiness of DNT IVB","method":"DNT IVB hazard classification"}}
{"id":"clm_7c1edb545736cc15","text":"The headline estimate is stable across independent proposals at roughly a quarter of control animals saved, the clinical analogue of Bayesian control-borrowing delivers comparable enrolment reductions, and the infrastructure — curated databases holding tens of thousands of control animals across decades of studies — already exists at scale, so the bottleneck is acceptance and stewardship rather than data volume.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_7c1edb545736cc15","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"toxicity-study control animals; Bayesian control-borrowing in trials","model":"toxicity-study control animals; historical-control databases (eTRANSAFE, RITA)","outcome":"Bayesian control-borrowing in trials; reduction via data reuse and stewardship bottleneck","method":"virtual control groups / control borrowing; historical-control databases (eTRANSAFE, RITA)"}}
{"id":"clm_7c4c4fd2a36ac57f","text":"Cross-ontology audits find over 1,900 logical nonalignments between core biomedical ontologies.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_7c4c4fd2a36ac57f","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7ca06cf1b52935ab","text":"Factorial designs, in which each animal contributes information on every factor and interactions become detectable, cut numbers in routine drug screens without loss of validity; accounting for the correlation among cage-mates lets experiments use more cages but fewer animals while gaining power; and case-study treatments of experimental design stress that there is no single optimum, only reasoned trade-offs between internal and external validity that must themselves be reported.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_7ca06cf1b52935ab","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7cb7b65a1e348f10","text":"The corrective apparatus is itself compromised, with systematic reviews and meta-analyses now mass-produced and, in the judgement of one bibliometric survey, largely redundant, misleading, or conflicted, even as the preclinical literature expands faster than systematic review can track it.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_7cb7b65a1e348f10","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7cdb70a617cd9c53","text":"The contrast is sharp within neuroimaging: a purpose-built FAIR archive organised around the enforced Brain Imaging Data Structure documents substantial realized reuse, with 165 downstream publications identified that reused its datasets.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_7cdb70a617cd9c53","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7d8ace4de74bf436","text":"The data that would let this record be checked or reused are largely absent — only about half of animal experiments are ever published, and only around 2% of medical papers actually share their data against the roughly 8% that declare they do.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_7d8ace4de74bf436","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal experiments publication; medical data availability","model":"animal experiments publication; data sharing","outcome":"medical data availability; knowledge unavailable for reuse","method":"declared vs actual data sharing; data sharing"}}
{"id":"clm_7dd72270ce35fea3","text":"That nomenclature is neither complete nor static: forum opinions note gaps requiring new terms for medical-device studies, revisions continue to appear a decade after the original tissue publications, and satellite symposia have documented cases where neither INHAND nor SEND contained a term matching an observed lesion.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_7dd72270ce35fea3","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7dfefc334b5854a2","text":"Universal open-raw-data mandates can themselves cause harm where they force qualitative or consent-sensitive material into an inappropriate mould.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_7dfefc334b5854a2","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7e6c54a6a5b607d2","text":"It is precisely the reframing of Reduction as a problem of design and reuse rather than of counting.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_7e6c54a6a5b607d2","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_7e8d223ccabb1493","text":"The opposing view argues that ranking instruments — global university rankings among them — are inherently incompatible with socially responsible practice and should be abandoned rather than repaired.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_7e8d223ccabb1493","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"rankings inherently incompatible with responsible practice","method":"ranking instruments / global university rankings"}}
{"id":"clm_7f075e51e79cd814","text":"Reviews trace this flood squarely to academic pressure and monetary publication incentives, and the same reward logic drives authorship inflation, gift and honorary authorship, salami-slicing, and citation gaming.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_7f075e51e79cd814","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"publication incentives drive fraud and gaming","method":"authorship inflation, gift authorship, salami-slicing, citation gaming"}}
{"id":"clm_7fec0200b431d303","text":"The downstream cost is illustrated concretely: in global-health data reuse, one analyst described spending some 80% of their time on cleaning and curation before any analysis could begin, and inconsistent metadata force researchers to spend over 40% of curation time on manual standardization.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_7fec0200b431d303","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: suggestive; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_807fa44df263d874","text":"Underlying all three is a single unmeasured link: the causal chain from a governance requirement, through actual data reuse, to fewer animals used has essentially never been quantified, so the review's central Reduction claim rests on a projection rather than a measurement, and building the infrastructure to measure it — standardised, FAIR control-animal data whose reuse can be tracked to an animal-count saving — is itself a research priority.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_807fa44df263d874","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal use (behavioral neuroscience; toxicology)","model":"animal use (behavioral neuroscience; toxicology); standardised FAIR control-animal data; reuse tracking","outcome":"the unmeasured causal link","method":"measuring Reduction; projection vs measurement; standardised FAIR control-animal data; reuse tracking"}}
{"id":"clm_80c863005999043b","text":"When licensing authorities screen applications, measures against bias are described at very low rates, leaving reviewers without the information a meaningful weighing requires.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_80c863005999043b","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_81018eb990627d11","text":"The usual justification — that females are intrinsically more variable — is unfounded: across 311 neuroscience studies female rats were no more variable than males, even without controlling for the oestrous cycle, yet male-only designs continue to distort conclusions in domains from morphine sensitisation to cough, and even a variable as basic as animal age is reported inconsistently.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_81018eb990627d11","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_811c0195178b7488","text":"Where external controls are used, retrospectively assembled natural-history data dominate — the most common source in 44% of one set of FDA approvals — and almost half of single-arm-trial applications were criticised for using external controls that were not contemporaneous with the trial.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_811c0195178b7488","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"FDA/EMA drug-biologic approvals with external controls","outcome":"FDA/EMA drug-biologic approvals with external controls; sourcing and non-contemporaneity of external controls","method":"retrospective natural-history controls; contemporaneity"}}
{"id":"clm_812bd4351ad01b13","text":"Even registered systematic-review protocols convert to publications only about half the time, and slowly.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_812bd4351ad01b13","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"systematic reviews of animal studies","model":"systematic reviews of animal studies","outcome":"publication follow-through / research waste","method":"PROSPERO protocol-to-publication tracking"}}
{"id":"clm_816e971fa896eb67","text":"Review-level syntheses treat FAIR as a demonstrated remedy while direct retrieval audits find most shared data incomplete or unusable, and scoring of the data that are shared returns low reusability sub-scores even in unrelated domains.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_816e971fa896eb67","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"health and dental research data","model":"FAIR data reusability scoring","outcome":"health and dental research data; FAIR remedy claims vs audited reality","method":"review synthesis vs retrieval audit; FAIR data reusability scoring"}}
{"id":"clm_819a6eb0bfb98486","text":"It remains open, and the interposed reviews suggest the truth is developmental — real capability, minimal regulated deployment, with data-sharing and standardisation named as the rate-limiting steps.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_819a6eb0bfb98486","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"regulated-deployment status of MPS","method":"MPS standardisation & data-sharing"}}
{"id":"clm_81cadf0692867021","text":"That the framework is now statutory across the EU and beyond has not produced a single shared reading of it; a large multinational group documents that interpretations of each R vary substantially and shape statutory regimes in divergent, sometimes contradictory ways, and a close comparison of Swiss law with the original definitions finds a species-focused drift in Replacement that the authors argue undermines the principles in practice.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_81cadf0692867021","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_824bebb39bd91ce4","text":"Reformers have responded with a proliferation of instruments — the SYRCLE risk-of-bias tool adapted from Cochrane, the NINDS core reporting standards, planning-stage guidance, preregistration platforms, dozens of consolidated preclinical guideline documents offering scores of rigor recommendations, and formal frameworks for sample-size determination under the Reduction principle — yet more than twenty competing appraisal tools now exist, itself an obstacle to any standard judgement of quality.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_824bebb39bd91ce4","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"guideline proliferation","method":"preclinical rigor instruments / risk-of-bias tools"}}
{"id":"clm_829f80a895bab81c","text":"By March 2026, EMA had issued a draft qualification opinion for virtual controls in rat non-GLP dose-range-finding studies, a narrower context than pivotal toxicology studies.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_829f80a895bab81c","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"rats","model":"rats; virtual control groups replacing concurrent control groups","outcome":"regulatory status and scope as of March 2026","method":"EMA draft qualification for non-GLP dose-range-finding studies; virtual control groups replacing concurrent control groups"}}
{"id":"clm_82bb1f4c9cbfc5b9","text":"Project-level audits find the opposite: sharing at both the project and article level \"was not carried out in the majority of cases, and when sharing was accomplished, the shared data were often of questionable usability\".","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_82bb1f4c9cbfc5b9","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_8316afa2229e6b34","text":"The same tissue-engineering advances extend across tumour, lung, kidney, and retinal systems used for drug screening and disease modelling.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_8316afa2229e6b34","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"tumour/lung/kidney/retinal organoids & chips; drug screening & disease modelling","model":"tumour/lung/kidney/retinal organoids & chips","outcome":"drug screening & disease modelling","method":"tissue engineering / organ-on-chip"}}
{"id":"clm_83b609f44f43f93b","text":"Open-practice badges not only raised reported open data but made the reported data more likely to be actually available, correct, and complete, whereas audits of datasets archived under blanket mandates found most incomplete or unusable, and a blanket journal data-sharing requirement produced near-zero actual public data.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_83b609f44f43f93b","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"ecology/evolution dataset completeness; clinical-trial data availability under mandate","model":"ecology/evolution dataset completeness","outcome":"clinical-trial data availability under mandate; incentive design vs realised data usability","method":"open-data badges vs blanket mandates data quality"}}
{"id":"clm_8454381efc318e5e","text":"The most direct is the argument that welfare-focused Rs cannot on their own make research ethical, because research without sufficient scientific value is unethical regardless of how humanely it is conducted — the case for adding Robustness, Registration, and Reporting to yield a \"6R\" set, motivated by the observation that roughly half of animal studies are never reported at all.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_8454381efc318e5e","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_86453844590a7d31","text":"The standardisation-and-rigour school holds that reproducibility follows from rigour plus transparency — pre-specified analysis plans, tight control of variation, and active laboratory management, and that minimising nuisance variation reduces the number of animals required.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_86453844590a7d31","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_86d73ea0e2ba611f","text":"Even large curated efforts to attach identifiers reach a minority of the record, matching only about 36% of taxonomic names to publications across three databases, while on-demand DOI minting is still being retrofitted onto repositories that lacked it.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_86d73ea0e2ba611f","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_877485ddc7e707b6","text":"Institutional animal-ethics committees approve almost everything that reaches them — a finding that recurs across empirical studies of committee decision-making and raises direct public-trust concerns.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_877485ddc7e707b6","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"rubber-stamp approval / public trust","method":"ethics-committee decision-making"}}
{"id":"clm_87a21fcbb95c67f4","text":"A framework benchmarking VCGs against three four-week rat oral-toxicity studies asked whether reconstructed controls could reproduce the significant deviations and study conclusions obtained with real concurrent controls, and a retrospective application to twenty pilot studies reported that VCGs maintained toxicological power and biological relevance while reducing animal usage, explicitly in the context of the FDA Modernization Act 2.0.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_87a21fcbb95c67f4","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_87ba8e51e86218da","text":"Roughly 85% of biomedical research is estimated to be avoidably wasted, only a fraction of preclinical landmark findings reproduce, and the diagnostic value of the preclinical enterprise has been estimated at a positive predictive value below one-half — every point of which is paid in animal lives.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_87ba8e51e86218da","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"preclinical / animal research; biomedical research value","model":"preclinical / animal research","outcome":"biomedical research value; avoidable research waste","method":"reproducibility / positive predictive value"}}
{"id":"clm_881453b05c9904a3","text":"Ethical-review bodies, the lever closest to the animal, mostly lack the expertise and mandate to judge scientific merit or to check that a study is non-duplicative, effects are heterogeneous and frequently small, and field-wide sharing remains near the ~2% floor even as concentrated local stewardship at a single, actively managed institution can lift it severalfold without generalising.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_881453b05c9904a3","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research ethics review (IACUC)","model":"animal research ethics review (IACUC); data sharing (~2% floor)","outcome":"governance limits closest to the animal","method":"ethical review, non-duplication, local stewardship; data sharing (~2% floor)"}}
{"id":"clm_88fd873c87fb3284","text":"Multi-organoid and organ-on-chip constructs sustain high viability and organ-specific function — a liver–islet chip held roughly 99% and 96% cell viability over thirty days, self-organising heart organoids beat autonomously and modelled infarction, and liver-chips maintained hepatocyte function and detected drug-induced steatosis and hepatotoxicity.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_88fd873c87fb3284","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"human iPSC-derived liver/islet/heart organoids; drug-induced steatosis/hepatotoxicity detection in vitro","model":"human iPSC-derived liver/islet/heart organoids","outcome":"drug-induced steatosis/hepatotoxicity detection in vitro","method":"multi-organoid & organ-on-chip microfluidic platforms"}}
{"id":"clm_89227c23932c38b8","text":"Within the same institutional study, structured templates produced more policy-conformant plans than unstructured approaches.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_89227c23932c38b8","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"one US academic medical center","outcome":"one US academic medical center; NIH policy conformance","method":"structured versus unstructured DMSP templates"}}
{"id":"clm_8a550b210dc46de7","text":"Common data elements built on the same logic have likewise seen disappointingly low adoption and have not broadly solved interoperability, and community checklists remain, in the main, human-readable narratives rather than the machine-actionable models that verifiable reuse requires.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_8a550b210dc46de7","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_8b13d9cf00b2822b","text":"In a Parkinson's-disease animal-model review, 15 of 38 ARRIVE 2.0 items had compliance levels of 80–100%.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_8b13d9cf00b2822b","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"Parkinson's-disease animal models","model":"Parkinson's-disease animal models","outcome":"reporting quality","method":"ARRIVE 2.0 compliance review"}}
{"id":"clm_8ba24a34a7ca163d","text":"Publishing and endorsing ARRIVE produced no significant reporting gain in the Chagas literature (51% → 66%, p=0.26), while implementing a checklist at one journal produced a three-fold-greater improvement than at a matched journal without one.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_8ba24a34a7ca163d","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"Chagas + in vivo animal studies","model":"Chagas + in vivo animal studies","outcome":"enforcement vs passive efficacy","method":"passive endorsement vs implementation"}}
{"id":"clm_8c6c19d72299bd03","text":"Contemporaneous audits reach the same place from different specialties: only a small minority of critical-care studies reported a sample-size calculation or met a basic composite of welfare outcomes, image-integrity problems pervade whole animal literatures with correction rates near zero, and depression-model meta-analyses find that almost no authors will share their underlying data on request.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_8c6c19d72299bd03","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_8d1382cd82a7deac","text":"Uptake studies find open practices spreading only modestly and largely independent of local institutional support, and a pre-post evaluation captured the pattern exactly — engagement with open-science tooling rose sharply while concrete outputs such as preregistrations, protocols, and shared datasets remained essentially absent both before and after.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_8d1382cd82a7deac","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"engagement rises while concrete outputs lag","method":"open-practice uptake (preregistration, protocols, data sharing)"}}
{"id":"clm_8d93ed705a2c7277","text":"A standard multimodal analgesia regimen intended to reduce suffering instead drove strain-specific side effects severe enough to require euthanasia, so a refinement increased harm; a commonly used analgesic failed to prevent post-surgical pain even at high doses; and committees permit painful procedures under an \"ethics of uncertainty\" in which incomplete knowledge of analgesia, and fear of its effects on data, pushes researchers to withhold pain relief.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_8d93ed705a2c7277","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_8de1a686b561d0d0","text":"A mandatory, checked data-and-code policy pushed provision to nearly all manuscripts, confirming that the operative variable is verification rather than the requirement itself.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_8de1a686b561d0d0","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: established; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"ecology/evolution research (field provenance)","model":"ecology/evolution research (field provenance); data/code provision","outcome":"verification vs bare requirement","method":"mandatory checked data/code policy; verification; data/code provision"}}
{"id":"clm_8f148eff4ab81212","text":"The studies themselves are chronically underpowered, which both exaggerates the effects that reach significance and lowers the chance that a positive result is true.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_8f148eff4ab81212","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"neuroscience/preclinical studies","model":"neuroscience/preclinical studies","outcome":"effect exaggeration and positive-predictive value","method":"statistical power analysis"}}
{"id":"clm_8f9fcdc21685a8b4","text":"Yet the same tooling literature concedes that assessment instruments are often either too domain-specific or too generalist to return a concrete, interpretable FAIRness level, and machine-actionable metadata templates such as CEDAR were introduced precisely because the community-defined \"rich metadata\" the principles demand was rarely being supplied in practice.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_8f9fcdc21685a8b4","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
