{"id":"clm_a1ca49b3c2903f66","text":"Independent audits have repeatedly documented the same gaps: reporting of bias-reduction measures is limited across a random sample of life-science papers and is actually lower in high-impact journals; a cerebrovascular journal volume stated a primary hypothesis in only 30% of articles; animal papers in a critical-care journal justified their sample size in 10% of cases, randomised in 43%, and blinded in 23%, with a single paper reporting an effect size; plastic-surgery animal studies blinded outcome assessment in 21.4%; and surveys spanning India, Sri Lanka and large-animal stroke models confirm the shortfall is global rather than parochial.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_a1ca49b3c2903f66","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"in vivo / animal research publications","model":"in vivo / animal research publications","outcome":"global reporting deficits","method":"risk-of-bias reporting audits"}}
