{"id":"clm_a508f6e452c6ed17","text":"And the welfare cost is paid regardless: a retrospective harm–benefit analysis judged fewer than 7% of preclinical studies ethically permissible on their realised balance of harm and benefit, with analgesia unreported in the overwhelming majority.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_a508f6e452c6ed17","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"preclinical animal studies (drug classes; rats/rabbits/primates)","model":"preclinical animal studies (drug classes; rats/rabbits/primates)","outcome":"ethical permissibility of animal research","method":"welfare/analgesia and harm-benefit reporting"}}
{"id":"clm_a50a4602be73e14b","text":"A head-to-head comparison in adjuvant breast cancer found mixed replicability — some survival curves overlapped, others diverged — so real-world controls could not be assumed to reproduce randomised ones, and a real-world external control failed to reproduce a lung-cancer trial's hazard ratio (1.53 versus 0.91) until Bayesian borrowing from a historical control trial pulled the estimate back toward the randomised result.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_a50a4602be73e14b","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"adjuvant breast cancer; first-line metastatic NSCLC","outcome":"adjuvant breast cancer; first-line metastatic NSCLC; real-world controls do not reliably reproduce randomised ones","method":"RWD external control vs RCT; Bayesian borrowing correction"}}
{"id":"clm_a5a45ec9b0591c62","text":"External validity as a whole has advanced far less than internal-validity reporting, reviews routinely extrapolate preclinical results to patients without first appraising the animal studies' risk of bias, and translational failure is sometimes traceable to mismatches as mundane as clinical outcome instruments too blunt to capture the effects seen in animals, or to physics and dosimetry parameters that are left unreported in the majority of radiobiology papers and vary enough between institutions to require credentialing.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_a5a45ec9b0591c62","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_a5b2346ba8187963","text":"Against these, every unenforced regime underperforms: voluntary data-availability statements yield actual sharing in the low single digits, and near-universal statement compliance coexists with repository linking in only about a fifth of papers.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_a5b2346ba8187963","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"biomedical research","outcome":"biomedical research; unenforced vs enforced regimes","method":"voluntary data-availability statements"}}
{"id":"clm_a680f6bd534655f5","text":"Alternative allocation mechanisms are being trialled at the funder level — partial randomisation, or funding lotteries, among near-equivalent applications — precisely to blunt the metric competition that credit inflation feeds, while responsible-assessment frameworks attempt to translate reform principles into concrete evaluation practice.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_a680f6bd534655f5","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"reforms to blunt metric competition","method":"funding lotteries / partial randomisation; responsible-assessment frameworks (SCOPE, DORA)"}}
{"id":"clm_a70e4d51795170f3","text":"The research reagents on which animal studies depend are themselves poorly stewarded: manual curation could identify only 1,445 studies providing knockout-validated evidence for specific antibodies, a tiny fraction of those in use, and roughly 40% of antibodies cited in one literature remained non-findable, lacking persistent research-resource identifiers, until stock centres actively intervened.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_a70e4d51795170f3","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_a71241222761827e","text":"That the field itself deprioritises this data-facing R is part of the problem: surveys find researchers invert the original ordering, treating Refinement as the higher priority and Replacement as barely possible, so Reduction sits neglected in the middle.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_a71241222761827e","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal-research 3Rs prioritisation","model":"animal-research 3Rs prioritisation","outcome":"inversion of the 3Rs hierarchy","method":"researcher attitude surveys"}}
