{"id":"clm_a95bbd57e1daa505","text":"Layered on top of this biological variability is measurement variability: a review of in vivo toxicology found rodent carcinogenicity outcomes only moderately replicable — 65–86% between sexes of one species and 36–74% between rat and mouse — which caps how well any historical comparison can perform.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_a95bbd57e1daa505","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_a96fad79a5992e49","text":"Underpinning all of this is chronic low power: the average neuroscience study is badly underpowered, which both inflates the effect sizes that do reach significance and lowers the probability that a positive result is true, and across disciplines statistical power has persistently sat below 50% while only about 13% of trials report outcomes fully consistent with their pre-registered commitments.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_a96fad79a5992e49","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"neuroscience studies","model":"neuroscience studies","outcome":"power & reliability","method":"statistical power"}}
{"id":"clm_aab87f9df3c38692","text":"Simulations show that even a single flexible-analysis strategy can lift the false-positive rate from five percent to at least thirty, drawing on a catalogue of thirty-four researcher degrees of freedom available in designing, running, and reporting a study.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_aab87f9df3c38692","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"simulation of false-positive inflation","outcome":"analytic flexibility inflates false positives","method":"p-hacking / researcher degrees of freedom; simulation of false-positive inflation"}}
{"id":"clm_aac4f9d25f9eb5c8","text":"The interventions are not obviously working — an exploratory survey concluded a culture of care is not yet fully established despite two decades of promotion, and the first multi-year controlled trial of resiliency programmes found no significant change in professional quality of life, a negative result worth stating plainly.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_aac4f9d25f9eb5c8","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
