{"id":"clm_af247dfcbbd8cc84","text":"The 3Rs already require that studies use no more animals than the knowledge requires and report enough for that knowledge to be trusted, and audits show both requirements are met only in a small minority of studies.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_af247dfcbbd8cc84","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal-research 3Rs compliance","model":"animal-research 3Rs compliance","outcome":"3Rs Reduction and reporting requirements","method":"sample-size and welfare reporting audits"}}
{"id":"clm_af562e6a471544c0","text":"The reuse of control data is itself double-edged, moreover: the same historical database can be marshalled to dismiss a marginal tumour finding as within the historical range or to support it as exceeding that range, a reminder that reuse without disciplined, outlier-robust method can mislead as readily as it can save animals.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_af562e6a471544c0","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"rodent lifetime carcinogenicity (rats, mice)","model":"rodent lifetime carcinogenicity (rats, mice); historical control databases","outcome":"reuse as double-edged","method":"outlier-robust reuse of historical controls; historical control databases"}}
