{"id":"clm_b244e5bffe44e13a","text":"The complementary strategy is not to reduce the animals but to replace them, avoiding their use in the first place — a logic already visible where computational models calibrated on prior animal data, such as digital-twin cardiotoxicity simulation, stand in for live control and treated animals.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_b244e5bffe44e13a","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"preclinical swine doxorubicin cardiotoxicity","model":"preclinical swine doxorubicin cardiotoxicity; digital-twin / computational heart models","outcome":"replace rather than reduce animal use","method":"in silico replacement of control and treated animals; digital-twin / computational heart models"}}
{"id":"clm_b25ccb1e9c7ad497","text":"Expert-rule and QSAR software predicted phototoxicity with 77% overall accuracy, a machine-learning model classified the pregnancy-risk category of 97 antibiotics with 94.11% external-validation accuracy, and interspecies aquatic-toxicity models passed cross-validation in more than three-quarters of cases.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_b25ccb1e9c7ad497","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"aquatic organisms; drug pregnancy risk; drug pregnancy-risk categorisation","model":"aquatic organisms; drug pregnancy risk; in silico QSAR / expert-rule / ML","outcome":"drug pregnancy-risk categorisation; NAM predictive accuracy","method":"in silico prediction validation; in silico QSAR / expert-rule / ML"}}
{"id":"clm_b31d93da4ecf6ba0","text":"Scoping the field, found compassion fatigue the most frequently described work-related stress yet no study empirically linking that stress to research quality, and surveys document the fatigue at scale: most laboratory-animal personnel report having experienced it, poorer professional quality of life tracks less enrichment, physical euthanasia methods, and less control over performing euthanasia, and staff attribute the strain more to institutional culture than to the animal work itself.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_b31d93da4ecf6ba0","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
