{"id":"clm_b954aa3602e3e3bd","text":"The pattern is that controls derived from prior randomised trials are comparatively trustworthy while those assembled from routine real-world data are not, and the burden of covariate adjustment for the latter is heavy — one external-control effort screened more than 120 potential confounders.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_b954aa3602e3e3bd","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"oncology external controls (RCT-derived vs RWD)","outcome":"oncology external controls (RCT-derived vs RWD); RCT-derived controls more trustworthy than RWD-derived","method":"covariate adjustment burden (>120 confounders)"}}
{"id":"clm_b96d3c255c7e8938","text":"The evidence that stewardship can be made to count is itself real but narrow, concentrated on the interventions that were enforced and checked rather than merely urged.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_b96d3c255c7e8938","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"in vivo / life-sciences research","model":"in vivo / life-sciences research","outcome":"incentives & enforcement","method":"enforced transparency interventions (checklists, badges)"}}
{"id":"clm_b97b249e4ba43f84","text":"Failure to share research biospecimens and data diverts funds into duplicate cohorts and deters reproducibility assessment; cancer heterogeneity means single centres cannot generate enough data for accurate models, which was part of the original motivation for FAIR in the first place.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_b97b249e4ba43f84","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_b9e4c2afdec0507c","text":"The reporting standards that would make an in vivo experiment reusable are unevenly adopted: the zebrafish community has not widely adopted data or metadata standards, so husbandry, imaging, and toxicology reporting remain inconsistent and reproducibility suffers, and traumatic-brain-injury translation is dominated by unpublished \"dark data\" from small, heterogeneous studies that never enter a findable record.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_b9e4c2afdec0507c","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
