{"id":"clm_bba58a80f795a50d","text":"Yet an audit of NSF-funded projects that had filed data-management plans found that 76% received an overall data-sharing score of zero, and that when sharing did occur the data were often of questionable usability owing to access, documentation, and formatting problems.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_bba58a80f795a50d","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_bc0c549d5a40139d","text":"In an international sample of biomedical promotion and tenure guidelines, found that peer-reviewed publications were mentioned as a criterion in almost every institution while data sharing appeared in only one percent and open-access publishing or registration in none; a matching study of research-intensive North American universities showed the Journal Impact Factor written explicitly into review, promotion, and tenure at a substantial minority of institutions, concentrated overwhelmingly at the most research-intensive campuses and framed in supportive terms.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_bc0c549d5a40139d","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"evaluation privileges publications over open practices","method":"RPT evaluation criteria (JIF, data sharing, open access)"}}
{"id":"clm_bc5052fe1cc3f0e4","text":"High-throughput and in silico streams generate large, heterogeneous datasets that re-create the same stewardship debt unless they are made FAIR from the outset — a point the NAM community has itself begun to press, arguing that findable, comparable data are not best practice but a prerequisite for trustworthy model outputs.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_bc5052fe1cc3f0e4","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"high-throughput and in-silico NAM datasets","outcome":"stewardship debt and trustworthy model outputs","method":"FAIR data stewardship for NAMs; high-throughput and in-silico NAM datasets"}}
{"id":"clm_bc8296226e34b6e4","text":"Concrete inefficiencies compound the neglect: male-only study designs generate surpluses of unused female animals in breeding colonies, a Reduction failure at the facility level that no amount of within-experiment refinement addresses.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_bc8296226e34b6e4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_bd0dd9963aa327ec","text":"A standing objection to Reduction is that it fights reproducibility: rigid standardisation to minimise variance produces results that do not generalise, so cutting animal numbers might buy fragility.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_bd0dd9963aa327ec","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_bf08de80a0bf26dc","text":"The precedent is double-edged and therefore instructive: mandates that are tracked and attributed to identifiable actors move compliance, but the same mandates left unaudited decay into the same low reporting rates that plague preclinical work, and registry-publication discrepancies remain common.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_bf08de80a0bf26dc","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"clinical trial registration/reporting","outcome":"clinical trial registration/reporting; double-edged governance precedent","method":"registry mandate enforcement / discrepancies"}}
{"id":"clm_bf8871bb74ed0850","text":"Subjective surveys of researchers estimate that only ~50% of experiments are published, whereas empirical tracking of registered protocols to publication finds rates closer to 70%.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_bf8871bb74ed0850","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"laboratory-animal research","model":"laboratory-animal research","outcome":"non-publication","method":"publication-rate estimation (survey vs tracking)"}}
{"id":"clm_c04b93392473716a","text":"Cross-national surveys find awareness of the reproducibility problem near-universal even where successful replication remains rare, coordinated replication efforts in fields beyond psychology continue to report low success rates, and where open practices are becoming normative it is so far within isolated subfields rather than across the system.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_c04b93392473716a","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"awareness-vs-practice gap across fields","method":"replication success rates; open-practice normativity"}}
{"id":"clm_c068a1b530c36211","text":"Barrier analyses converge on a persistent set of scientific, technical, economic, and cultural obstacles that keep NAMs out of routine decision-making; many candidate methods exist but very few have been adopted for regulatory use; and the field lacks standardised validation and acceptance criteria, so quality assurance has a structural blind spot.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_c068a1b530c36211","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"regulatory adoption barriers (scientific/economic/cultural)","method":"NAM validation & acceptance criteria"}}
{"id":"clm_c0a0d32caa8f0c30","text":"Capacity varies enormously — pan-African and Swedish surveys document limited oversight infrastructure and researchers markedly less positive toward the 3Rs than veterinarians, and communication gaps undermine the culture of care that welfare bodies are meant to sustain, even as researchers themselves criticise the practice of using extra animals simply to strengthen the statistics needed for a high-ranked publication — a direct line from publication pressure to animal cost.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_c0a0d32caa8f0c30","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research / 3Rs","model":"animal research / 3Rs","outcome":"publication pressure translating to animal cost","method":"oversight-capacity and culture-of-care surveys"}}
{"id":"clm_c0a2abb5f4dd5265","text":"NAM validation is often anchored to concordance with animal data that were themselves never validated for human relevance and are only moderately reproducible, so the yardstick is shaky.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_c0a2abb5f4dd5265","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"rodent carcinogenicity/endocrine bioassays","model":"rodent carcinogenicity/endocrine bioassays","outcome":"circular validation and human relevance","method":"NAM validation against animal-data concordance"}}
{"id":"clm_c0f2565b73248aa7","text":"The most-repeated figures — the modelled tens-of-billions irreproducibility cost, the \"most research is wasted\" synthesis, even the specific industry-reproducibility percentages — rest on modelled or non-transparent inputs and are best read as order-of-magnitude claims rather than measurements, a caution we have flagged wherever they appear.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_c0f2565b73248aa7","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"economic/waste models","outcome":"order-of-magnitude vs measurement","method":"modelled cost/waste estimates and transparency; economic/waste models"}}
{"id":"clm_c1292134bfc1f42e","text":"Redundant, misleading, or conflicted syntheses are mass-produced far faster than the primary research they digest, undetected software and computation errors propagate silently into published results, and a bibliometric mapping of the waste literature itself reveals a large and fast-growing field of concern.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_c1292134bfc1f42e","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"software/computation errors in published results","outcome":"the research-waste literature is large and fast-growing","method":"systematic-review overproduction; research-waste bibliometrics; software/computation errors in published results"}}
{"id":"clm_c150da83fe05ed23","text":"The same gap between a standard's promise and its semantic reach recurs at the level of metadata registries: the ISO/IEC 11179 model is presented as automatically conferring FAIR adherence across findability, interoperability, and reusability, yet a variable-level harmonisation effort across cardiovascular cohorts found that it supplies only a general registry framework and lacks the formal semantic relationships needed to align variables across studies.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_c150da83fe05ed23","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_c28c90fb5fed5c6e","text":"Accessibility is not uniform either: contrary to the assumption that a repository deposit makes data equally reachable to all, access to open-science resources varies by country through connectivity failures and outright blocking, the advanced services that make data usable depend on intrinsically limited computational resources that will be rationed rather than free, and community-owned \"diamond\" infrastructures are emerging in part because commercial routes leave many researchers without genuine access.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_c28c90fb5fed5c6e","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_c2d644434ce16083","text":"A retrospective harm–benefit analysis of preclinical research found that, weighing the animals' actual harms against the actual clinical benefit their studies produced, fewer than 7% of the studies examined would have been ethically permissible, and that 97% did not even report whether the animals received analgesia.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_c2d644434ce16083","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"preclinical animal research harms and analgesia reporting; clinical benefit derived from preclinical studies","model":"preclinical animal research harms and analgesia reporting","outcome":"clinical benefit derived from preclinical studies; ethical permissibility of animal research","method":"retrospective harm-benefit weighting"}}
{"id":"clm_c38e135a27e2e78f","text":"These are exactly the high-dimensional outputs that showed accumulate faster than they are curated, and the trend is toward more data, not less: high-throughput exposure methods deliberately expand chemical coverage far beyond what traditional assessment reached, while every mechanistic screen that maps assays onto adverse outcome pathways adds another layer of results that must be stored, versioned, and made interpretable to be reused.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_c38e135a27e2e78f","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"high-dimensional HTS/exposure data storage and versioning","outcome":"data accumulate faster than curation capacity","method":"high-throughput exposure methods and AOP-mapping screens; high-dimensional HTS/exposure data storage and versioning"}}
{"id":"clm_c41a0b7adbdf2dd0","text":"The timing of publication compounds the problem for animal work specifically: across 47 novel drugs, 87% of accessible animal efficacy studies appeared only after the first human trial had been published, and for 17% of the drugs no efficacy study was published before that trial at all — so the animal evidence, when it exists, frequently cannot have informed the decision to test in people.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_c41a0b7adbdf2dd0","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"preclinical animal efficacy studies; first-in-human trials","model":"preclinical animal efficacy studies","outcome":"first-in-human trials; translational sequence","method":"publication-timing analysis"}}
{"id":"clm_c43ff2d9c5138be3","text":"Two of these largest documented enforcement effects come from a psychology journal and an ecology journal; the strongest strictly animal-specific enforcement evidence — the Nature-journals revision mandate and the checklist-implementing journal — is real but more modest, so part of the case for enforcement is transferred into the animal context from adjacent fields.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_c43ff2d9c5138be3","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal-specific enforcement (Nature mandate, checklist journal)","model":"animal-specific enforcement (Nature mandate, checklist journal)","outcome":"cross-field transfer of the enforcement case","method":"enforcement-evidence provenance"}}
{"id":"clm_c4ec854c82d44ccc","text":"On cumulative harm, a fifteen-year database of blood markers from thirty-nine rhesus monkeys found no support for long-term cumulative effects of implants, fluid control, and repeated procedures, and is offered as a reassuring reference for severity assessment; against this, telomere attrition is proposed as an objective, dose-dependent molecular record of an animal's lifetime negative experience — a biomarker that would, by construction, register cumulative wear that conventional blood markers miss.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_c4ec854c82d44ccc","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_c5b4d84c46bcacf3","text":"The reproducibility literature independently prices the reliability side of the same failure: a probability-bounds economic model puts the cumulative preclinical irreproducibility rate above half and attaches a modelled cost of tens of billions of dollars a year to it in the United States alone, a figure that sits within broader accountings of avoidable research waste that reach a widely repeated — and, we will argue, over-cited — estimate that most biomedical research investment is squandered, and that is consistent with a theoretical prior holding that, under realistic assumptions about power and bias, most published research claims are more likely false than true.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_c5b4d84c46bcacf3","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"probability-bounds economic modelling of irreproducibility","outcome":"research waste and reliability of published findings","method":"meta-research on research waste and false-findings priors; probability-bounds economic modelling of irreproducibility"}}
{"id":"clm_c610f5bf953c42aa","text":"Among highly cited clinical studies, 16% were later contradicted and another 16% had initially overstated effects; even after refutation by randomised trials, half of the articles citing contradicted observational claims remained favourable; and citation-network analysis has shown how a belief unsupported by primary data can accumulate hundreds of thousands of supporting citation paths and thereby manufacture unfounded authority.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_c610f5bf953c42aa","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_c614f728d46564b1","text":"The regulatory infrastructure appears to be following: industry surveys report NAM-based filings replacing large-animal studies and being accepted by health authorities, workshops have identified routes to waive the 90-day dog study, read-across is an internationally recognised validated method — including NAM-enhanced read-across advanced by EU consortia — with category-based submissions accepted at about 62%, and the US FDA Modernization Acts now permit microphysiological systems alongside or instead of animals in investigational filings, and higher-complexity three-dimensional models are being positioned to align with the FDA's stated intent to phase out animal testing for certain drugs.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_c614f728d46564b1","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"medicinal-product filings / IND submissions","outcome":"medicinal-product filings / IND submissions; regulatory acceptance (EMA/ICH, FDA Modernization Acts)","method":"read-across, MPS, NAM regulatory filings"}}
{"id":"clm_c629850b7a5b4651","text":"Proposals to add a formal benefit-assessment step to committee review collide with exactly this doubt about feasibility.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_c629850b7a5b4651","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_c657aafc7eac0002","text":"Male animals have dominated biomedical research, most severely in neuroscience where single-sex male studies once outnumbered female ones 5.5 to 1; a decade after this was quantified, both-sex inclusion had risen across nine disciplines but the proportion actually analysing data by sex had not, in eight of them, despite a US policy expecting sex to be treated as a biological variable.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_c657aafc7eac0002","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_c67d1a468e78766b","text":"The toolkit is by now deep: foundational power and meta-analytic-predictive priors, along with probability- or distance-based variants that cap how much is borrowed, have been developed and simulated across binary, count and time-to-event endpoints, and their adaptive descendants tie the borrowed quantity to observed heterogeneity or covariate consistency in an effort to preserve error control when sources disagree.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_c67d1a468e78766b","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"clinical-trial control borrowing","model":"simulation across binary/count/time-to-event endpoints","outcome":"clinical-trial control borrowing; deep, error-control-oriented borrowing toolkit","method":"power / MAP / distance-based / adaptive priors; simulation across binary/count/time-to-event endpoints"}}
