{"id":"clm_cab3ea7f5f231c1e","text":"The first meta-analysis of misconduct surveys estimated that around two percent of scientists admit fabricating or falsifying data at least once, with up to a third admitting other questionable practices; a five-country study found that almost all researchers admit using at least one such practice, though measured frequency of any specific practice is far lower; and an implicit-association study found that about a fifth of scientists tacitly associate questionable practices with career success while very few connect outright fabrication to success.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_cab3ea7f5f231c1e","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"distinct prevalences of fabrication, QRPs, and success-association","method":"misconduct/QRP surveys and implicit-association test"}}
{"id":"clm_cae2995388dc0a48","text":"Using data from 440 preclinical studies across 13 interventions, single-laboratory experiments failed to predict the true effect size in more than half of cases even when powered above 0.8, and — counter to the intuition that bigger is better — larger single-lab samples made effect-size estimates less accurate, whereas distributing animals across laboratories improved them.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_cae2995388dc0a48","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_cb442711d183b946","text":"One strand frames microphysiological systems as bioengineering organ architecture and function so as to revolutionise drug development, reduce animal testing, and enable personalised medicine.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_cb442711d183b946","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: speculation; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"MPS organ architecture/function; drug development, personalised medicine","model":"MPS organ architecture/function","outcome":"drug development, personalised medicine; transformative promise of MPS","method":"microphysiological systems"}}
{"id":"clm_cc73fb9a2fccdae0","text":"The clinical-trial guideline family has meanwhile entered a phase of rapid extension — CONSORT 2025 and SPIRIT 2025 added open-science sections and new items through 317-participant Delphi processes, and a proliferation of specialised offshoots now covers overviews of reviews, large-language-model studies, outcome reporting, code availability, conflicts and funding, neurostimulation devices, and acupuncture case reports.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_cc73fb9a2fccdae0","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"clinical-trial reporting guidelines","model":"LLM-study reporting (TRIPOD-LLM)","outcome":"clinical-trial reporting guidelines; guideline proliferation","method":"CONSORT/SPIRIT 2025 and extensions; LLM-study reporting (TRIPOD-LLM)"}}
{"id":"clm_cd0844a346f002ad","text":"The manifesto for reproducible science argues that measures targeting methods, reporting, reproducibility, evaluation, and incentives — supported by simulation and early empirical evidence — can make research more reliable given iterative adoption by researchers, institutions, funders, and journals.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_cd0844a346f002ad","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"iterative multi-stakeholder adoption improves reliability","method":"reproducibility reform measures (methods/reporting/evaluation/incentives)"}}
{"id":"clm_cf9848d69a0804a6","text":"These limits are why NAM outputs are typically embedded in weight-of-evidence and extrapolation workflows rather than used alone — a developmental-toxicity extrapolation found that using all in vitro assays, not the developmental subset, gave the most conservative human-equivalent dose, and a stem-cell-plus-modelling approach derived bisphenol-A reference doses close to a regulatory value without any animals.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_cf9848d69a0804a6","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"hESC toxicogenomics (BPA)","model":"hESC toxicogenomics (BPA); IVIVE, pregnancy-PBPK","outcome":"NAM integration workflows","method":"weight-of-evidence integration, developmental extrapolation; IVIVE, pregnancy-PBPK"}}
{"id":"clm_d06b06f8674669a7","text":"A recent EFSA opinion proposes a stepwise quantitative decision scheme to harmonise how historical and concurrent control data are compiled and combined.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_d06b06f8674669a7","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d0e606c2995a9b49","text":"Standardised disease models and open-research practice — preregistration, preprints, and data management planned from the outset — are being promoted in parallel to make the resulting data reusable rather than merely deposited.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_d0e606c2995a9b49","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal disease models","model":"animal disease models","outcome":"open-research practice promotion","method":"preregistration / preprints / data management"}}
{"id":"clm_d10097cb67d497d2","text":"Third, the incentive and appraisal system must reward stewardship, following proposals to assess researchers on responsible practice and to make funders accountable for the waste they finance.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_d10097cb67d497d2","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"incentives should reward stewardship; funder accountability","method":"researcher assessment / preregistration proposals"}}
{"id":"clm_d142fe84b94cfac3","text":"The levers are not scarce — hundreds of reporting guidelines already exist, and ARRIVE was even reorganised into an \"Essential 10\" after a decade of endorsement failed to lift reporting — so the binding constraint is enforcement, not the absence of a standard.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_d142fe84b94cfac3","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"in vivo animal research reporting","model":"in vivo animal research reporting","outcome":"enforcement as the binding constraint","method":"reporting guidelines; ARRIVE Essential 10; enforcement"}}
{"id":"clm_d1641e415807f27a","text":"Complementary instruments target the stages ARRIVE does not: the PREPARE guidelines address planning before an animal is touched, on the argument that better reporting cannot repair work that was badly designed in the first place, while REFLECT extends the CONSORT template to livestock and food-safety trials.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_d1641e415807f27a","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal / livestock research; livestock/food-safety RCTs","model":"animal / livestock research","outcome":"livestock/food-safety RCTs; planning vs reporting stages of rigor","method":"PREPARE and REFLECT guidelines"}}
{"id":"clm_d1d648dfef20c988","text":"Systematic reviews of over a thousand direct comparisons find that environmentally enriched animals are not more variable than barren-housed ones — sometimes less — refuting the claim that welfare-improving housing undermines standardisation, a result anticipated by earlier work showing enrichment raised neither individual variability nor the risk of conflicting replicate outcomes.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_d1d648dfef20c988","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d1fdc83be45059ec","text":"And reuse of existing data, alongside the outputs of non-animal methods, extends Replacement, substituting stored knowledge and in vitro or in silico results for live animals.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_d1fdc83be45059ec","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d2206d1ef62fe0b8","text":"A scoping review of interventions to incentivise sharing screened over a thousand papers and identified only a modest set of tested levers; at a different level entirely — and outside the animal-data scope of this review — the motivations of the individuals whose data are shared, whether financial or altruistic, are a distinct determinant of participation that generic institutional incentives do not touch.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_d2206d1ef62fe0b8","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d2528c94c6435682","text":"In idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, external controls built from historical randomised-trial placebo arms reproduced the original treatment effect, whereas controls built from registry or electronic-health-record data did not.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_d2528c94c6435682","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis trials","outcome":"idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis trials; source-dependent reproducibility of external controls","method":"external controls from RCT placebo vs registry/EHR"}}
{"id":"clm_d272fa77ba6d556a","text":"The declared-versus-actual gap is itself the primary evidence: a policy requirement to state a data-sharing intention produced almost no usable public data, and the same attitude-behaviour gap recurs among the gatekeepers, where most journal editors endorse transparency guidelines yet do not prioritise or intend to implement them.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_d272fa77ba6d556a","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"clinical-trial data-sharing declared vs actual","outcome":"clinical-trial data-sharing declared vs actual; attitude-behaviour gap among gatekeepers","method":"policy declaration vs realised data availability; editor intentions"}}
{"id":"clm_d2bed32ff25670f4","text":"The TRUST Principles frame repository trustworthiness as something to be earned and demonstrated through external assessment, yet a content analysis of 91 certified repositories concluded that, although hundreds of Trustworthy Digital Repositories are certified, there is no evidence that certification actually improves preservation, and an instrument applied to eight biomedical repositories found little explicit acknowledgment of open, FAIR, citable, or trustworthy principles even where the underlying practices were present.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_d2bed32ff25670f4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d2c0007a5dcc30b8","text":"Domain communities have added their own: common data elements for epilepsy pharmacology, minimum-information standards for humanised mice, welfare-focused behaviour-modification reporting, and behavioural-psychopharmacology considerations all aim to make studies comparable and reusable.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_d2c0007a5dcc30b8","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal models (mice, epilepsy, welfare)","model":"animal models (mice, epilepsy, welfare)","outcome":"comparability and reusability","method":"domain common-data-elements / minimum-information standards"}}
{"id":"clm_d2f000d937987a87","text":"The system is not even structured to notice: audits of ethical-review decisions find the legally required harm–benefit weighing frequently absent or confused, and measures against bias described at very low rates, so the authorising body cannot see the scientific validity on which its own justification depends.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_d2f000d937987a87","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal-experiment ethical review","model":"animal-experiment ethical review","outcome":"governance adequacy","method":"harm-benefit analysis and bias-measure reporting"}}
{"id":"clm_d35f1d8d894cc20e","text":"The clinical literature supplies the most concrete measurements: spin — reporting that misrepresents nonsignificant results as favourable — appears in roughly half to three-quarters of nonsignificant randomised-trial reports across general medicine, urology, bariatric, vascular, and emergency-medicine specialties, with industry funding raising the odds.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_d35f1d8d894cc20e","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"spin in nonsignificant RCT reports across 5 specialties","outcome":"spin in nonsignificant RCT reports across 5 specialties","method":"misrepresentation of nonsignificant results; industry funding raises odds"}}
{"id":"clm_d4208ff8a79259e1","text":"Where improvement has occurred it has been uneven: a nationwide comparison found randomisation reporting rose from 24.0% to 40.8% between 2009 and 2018 while conflict-of-interest disclosure jumped from 37.6% to 90.4%, but a survey of in-vivo researchers still found fewer than half claiming to use blinded outcome assessment, and a commentary across twenty recent preclinical reviews found that not one study scored above eight of ten on a standard quality scale, with a median of four.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_d4208ff8a79259e1","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"preclinical animal publications","model":"preclinical animal publications","outcome":"uneven improvement","method":"reporting trends & quality scores"}}
{"id":"clm_d422ccc8064b9d47","text":"Opinion surveys of laboratory-animal researchers put the published fraction low: staff at not-for-profit institutes estimated that only half of conducted animal experiments are published, and those in for-profit settings estimated just 10%.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_d422ccc8064b9d47","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"laboratory-animal research (survey)","model":"laboratory-animal research (survey)","outcome":"file-drawer / non-publication","method":"publication-rate estimation"}}
{"id":"clm_d4e29970066383a5","text":"External control arms — the clinical analogue of VCGs — are now visibly present in regulatory decisions: they featured in 17% of EMA cancer-drug approvals from 2016 to 2021, with a 63% acceptance rate among submissions that used them, and nearly half of recent multiple-myeloma approvals leveraged real-world evidence.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_d4e29970066383a5","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"EMA/FDA oncology and multiple-myeloma approvals","outcome":"EMA/FDA oncology and multiple-myeloma approvals; regulatory adoption of external controls","method":"external control arms / RWE in regulatory submissions"}}
{"id":"clm_d51eafef2cf20797","text":"The programme on increasing value and reducing waste located waste at every stage from question selection to inaccessible reporting, arguing that trial and review output already outpaces any capacity to synthesise it and that full information is available for only about half of all studies.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_d51eafef2cf20797","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"clinical trials and systematic reviews","outcome":"clinical trials and systematic reviews; waste at every research stage; output outpaces synthesis capacity","method":"research waste across stages; reporting accessibility"}}
{"id":"clm_d5ab2c0e1cedefcc","text":"report that nearly half of surveyed scientists do not make their data electronically available and develop a six-category model concluding that data behave not as a shared commons but as a private asset whose release requires positive incentives that do not exist.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_d5ab2c0e1cedefcc","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"electronic data availability","outcome":"data behave as a private asset requiring positive incentives","method":"data-sharing behaviour survey; electronic data availability"}}
{"id":"clm_d61fd203c186198a","text":"Governance constraints of a different kind bind the ordinary case too: privacy regulation such as GDPR can directly contradict open-data mandates, and human genomic and biospecimen repositories frequently operate under managed rather than open access for exactly this reason.","section":"sec-fair-preclinical","anchor":"content/04_fair_preclinical_data.md#clm_d61fd203c186198a","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d6a13bd337f06199","text":"The stewardship burden is concrete: nanosafety groups offer eight specific recommendations for capturing metadata at the point of generation and argue for dedicated data-shepherd roles precisely because retrofitting metadata later routinely fails.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_d6a13bd337f06199","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"model":"metadata capture at point of data generation","outcome":"retrofitting metadata fails; dedicated data-shepherd roles needed","method":"data stewardship / metadata reporting practices; metadata capture at point of data generation"}}
{"id":"clm_d6cf9d2fa8c1532b","text":"A randomised controlled trial that asked authors to complete an ARRIVE checklist at submission found that no manuscript in either arm achieved full compliance, and only a single sub-item — animal husbandry — improved at all.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_d6cf9d2fa8c1532b","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"in vivo animal research","model":"in vivo animal research","outcome":"checklist efficacy","method":"ARRIVE-checklist-at-submission RCT"}}
{"id":"clm_d85a2138d708eea4","text":"The empirical backdrop favours neither complacency: authorisation decisions have been shown to rest on confidence rather than evidence of scientific rigour, only 6 of 30 European countries have produced any guidance to support the analysis, and scoping reviews of decision tools find sparse resources and recommend deliberation over scoring.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_d85a2138d708eea4","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d8a33a0e3eb9971d","text":"Extending the 3Rs to the wellbeing of the people who do the work, and building safe channels such as incident-reporting systems, are efforts to make that stewardship a lived norm rather than a poster.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_d8a33a0e3eb9971d","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d8af6013b0994af3","text":"Even reproducibility depends on governance reaching into husbandry and genetics that committees rarely inspect: published descriptions omitted the mutated allele sequence for 20 of 27 animal models at one institution.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_d8af6013b0994af3","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"GM mouse models / genetic provenance","model":"GM mouse models / genetic provenance","outcome":"reproducibility depends on husbandry/genetics governance","method":"reporting of mutated-allele sequence"}}
{"id":"clm_d8b6eea126fab680","text":"Several report quantitative concordance with humans: proximal-tubule chips estimate renal clearance within 10–20% of clinical values after scaling, a perfused tubule chip reproduced a 35% transporter-mediated permeability change with a reference inhibitor, a liver-microphysiological qualification review cites a reported 100% sensitivity and 90% specificity for drug-induced liver injury, an intestinal-organoid model coupled to kinetics matched clinical diarrhoea incidence for oncology drugs, and patient-derived colorectal organoids predicted individual cetuximab response with over 80% concordance.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_d8b6eea126fab680","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"tubule/liver/intestinal/colorectal organoids & chips; DILI, diarrhoea incidence, cetuximab response prediction","model":"tubule/liver/intestinal/colorectal organoids & chips; IVIVE / PBPK coupling","outcome":"DILI, diarrhoea incidence, cetuximab response prediction","method":"organ-on-chip clinical-concordance validation; IVIVE / PBPK coupling"}}
{"id":"clm_d8eb24c7e2456dc6","text":"Population drift in open platform trials that reuse non-concurrent controls can bias estimates and inflate Type I error; mismatched disease-assessment schedules between a synthetic control and its trial can cause severe error inflation or power loss unless harmonised; and even propensity-score-weighted priors can only attenuate, never eliminate, confounding bias from combining trial and external data.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_d8eb24c7e2456dc6","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"platform / synthetic-control trials","model":"simulation","outcome":"platform / synthetic-control trials; borrowing attenuates but cannot eliminate confounding","method":"population drift, non-concurrent controls, propensity-score priors; simulation"}}
{"id":"clm_d939fd709ae661f2","text":"Most damningly, a scoping review found that of more than a hundred studies of reproducibility interventions, only a handful measured reproducibility itself; the rest measured proxies presumed to help, and a matched comparison found preregistered studies no less likely to report positive results than their non-preregistered counterparts, even as they improved power.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_d939fd709ae661f2","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"outcome":"proxies measured instead of reproducibility itself","method":"reproducibility-intervention outcome measures; preregistration effect on positive results"}}
{"id":"clm_d97d55c061252a0b","text":"Prospective audits find outcome-switching pervasive and its disclosure rare, undeclared switching survives even direct correction letters, and a striking worked example shows an entire therapeutic conclusion evaporating once analysis is restricted to pre-registered primary outcomes.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_d97d55c061252a0b","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"outcome-switching prevalence and non-disclosure in clinical trials","outcome":"outcome-switching prevalence and non-disclosure in clinical trials","method":"pre-registered vs reported primary outcomes"}}
{"id":"clm_d9da8c9c3e2a5bdf","text":"Framed this way, the reuse of control data is not merely good data hygiene but a direct Reduction intervention, and several strands of the literature now treat efficient reuse of existing animal data as an ethical obligation rather than a convenience.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_d9da8c9c3e2a5bdf","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_d9df3c267ca4e38a","text":"The black-box character of many machine-learning components compounds the interpretability problem regulators must resolve before trusting these chains, and the developmental-neurotoxicity battery divides its own community.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_d9df3c267ca4e38a","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"machine-learning / QSAR components","outcome":"interpretability for regulatory trust","method":"PBPK/ML integration, DNT battery; machine-learning / QSAR components"}}
{"id":"clm_daff8f98969983c6","text":"It sits within a broader accounting of avoidable waste in an enterprise that consumed some US\\$240 billion globally in 2010 and close to a quarter of a trillion dollars annually thereafter, of which an oft-quoted 85% is judged to be squandered, and around which a consensus of meta-researchers holds that most new biomedical discoveries will not stand the test of time.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_daff8f98969983c6","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"biomedical research enterprise; clinical research quality","model":"biomedical research enterprise","outcome":"clinical research quality; avoidable waste & reliability","method":"research-waste accounting"}}
{"id":"clm_dbbbc12c97bbf7a2","text":"The multicentre design is no panacea, however: a preregistered, fully blinded three-site confirmatory trial of neuroprotectants for chemotherapy-induced neuropathy failed its primary objective when unexpected toxicity and tumour growth left it underpowered — evidence that distributed rigour exposes translational uncertainty rather than abolishing it.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_dbbbc12c97bbf7a2","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
