{"id":"clm_e0c77325a4876794","text":"The Reduction principle was never \"use the fewest animals\" but \"use no more animals than the knowledge requires,\" and reviews of the Reduction literature insist on exactly this: minimising numbers is a matter of correct design and statistics, since both too many and too few animals waste life and yield unreliable results, and the goal is not the smallest possible study but the right number, because excessive reduction produces underpowered, uninterpretable experiments.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_e0c77325a4876794","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: definition; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
