{"id":"clm_f4d18583dce340ef","text":"One position holds that in translational research replacement should be prioritised over all other considerations, treating animal models as an epistemically and ethically failing paradigm, a stance reinforced by regulatory roadmaps to reduce animal testing and steep growth in non-animal-method publications.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_f4d18583dce340ef","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_f56680694ea21665","text":"In a Wistar Han rat liver-enzyme analysis, 68.5% of concurrent-versus-virtual-control comparisons achieved at least 90% agreement in effect-size estimates.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_f56680694ea21665","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"Wistar Han rats","model":"Wistar Han rats; concurrent-versus-virtual control comparison","outcome":"endpoint-specific virtual-control concordance","method":"liver-enzyme effect-size agreement analysis; concurrent-versus-virtual control comparison"}}
{"id":"clm_f58551cb3da1250f","text":"On this reading, next-generation risk assessment using non-animal methods is, in defined settings, entirely appropriate today for assuring chemical safety; economic modelling projects that switching liver-based drug-induced liver injury evaluation to organ-on-chip could save roughly $3 billion annually; microphysiological systems are framed as already revolutionising drug development and reducing animal use; and a workshop demonstrated that a non-animal bioactivity-plus-kinetics battery gave protection equivalent to a stand-alone rat repeat-dose study across 46 benchmark exposures.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_f58551cb3da1250f","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"in silico + economic modelling","outcome":"regulatory readiness of NAMs","method":"NGRA / organ-on-chip / NAM bioactivity+kinetics battery; in silico + economic modelling"}}
{"id":"clm_f5d1b5a917155882","text":"The foundational meta-analytic-predictive approach quantifies exactly how much a historical control arm is worth: 930 control patients across eleven historical trials, with small heterogeneity, translated into a prior worth about ninety patients, and its extension to over-dispersed lesion counts valued 1,936 historical controls from nine multiple-sclerosis trials at a prior of about forty-five patients, meaning a new control arm could be shrunk by that many recruits.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_f5d1b5a917155882","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_f67dbe229cd952b2","text":"Spontaneous Leydig-cell adenoma incidence in control rats ranges from near 100% in F344 to 13.7% in Wistar and 4.2% in Sprague-Dawley, and is further modulated by breeder, diet and age; female mononuclear-cell leukaemia backgrounds differ roughly eighteen-fold between Sprague-Dawley and F344/N strains; pituitary adenomas and adrenal hyperplasias reach incidences well above half of animals in some strains and sexes; and body-weight and diet control alone shift terminal background liver-tumour incidence into a 15–20% band.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_f67dbe229cd952b2","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_f69e5387bae21951","text":"That completion figure — only 26% of the planned experiments could be carried out at all — is a feasibility ceiling rather than a replication rate, and as such is distinct from, though it sits alongside, the earlier industry audits in which an estimated 25% (Bayer) and 11% (Amgen) of findings could be reproduced.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_f69e5387bae21951","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"preclinical cancer biology & industry audits","model":"preclinical cancer biology & industry audits","outcome":"reproducibility metrics","method":"feasibility vs replication-rate distinction"}}
{"id":"clm_f736a082795f4964","text":"The Reproducibility Project: Psychology reported that only ~36% of replications were statistically significant.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_f736a082795f4964","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_f754fbc3935f5cda","text":"Brink and Lewis proposed a 12Rs framework spanning animal welfare, social values, and scientific integrity.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_f754fbc3935f5cda","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"animal welfare, social values, and scientific integrity","method":"12Rs framework"}}
{"id":"clm_f8469d0669ad56f7","text":"An evaluation of two decades of pesticide assessments found historical control data used almost exclusively to avoid false-positive calls, never to guard against false negatives, and typically without testing the assumption that current and historical controls share an underlying distribution.","section":"sec-virtual-controls","anchor":"content/05_virtual_control_groups.md#clm_f8469d0669ad56f7","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_f88a8b2eb442ae7f","text":"Their value is not their precision but their convergence with a theoretical prior — that under realistic assumptions about power, bias, and pre-study odds, a research claim in most fields is more likely false than true.","section":"sec-repro-crisis","anchor":"content/02_reproducibility_crisis.md#clm_f88a8b2eb442ae7f","claimType":"methodological","qualification":"Source claim type: methodological; modality: suggestive; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"model":"simulation","outcome":"false-findings prior / crisis narrative","method":"research-reliability theory; simulation"}}
{"id":"clm_f8a869f22be109d7","text":"Because Reduction was always a claim about information — use no more animals than the knowledge requires — a dataset that cannot be found, trusted, or reused is knowledge that must be regenerated, and the only way to regenerate knowledge from live tissue is to use more animals.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_f8a869f22be109d7","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal experiments / live tissue","model":"animal experiments / live tissue; historical-control simulation","outcome":"Reduction as a claim about information","method":"Reduction / experimental design and data reuse; historical-control simulation"}}
{"id":"clm_f96b7b78f9df42dd","text":"The link from unusable byte to used animal is not metaphorical but mechanical — it is the same link that makes historical-control reuse count as Reduction, that makes a continuously maintained living evidence summary a Reduction instrument because knowledge kept visible need not be regenerated, and that makes duplicate systematic reviews a waste worth pre-registration to prevent.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_f96b7b78f9df42dd","claimType":"mechanistic","qualification":"Source claim type: causal; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_fa90fc6d45f02c3a","text":"It is coloured by negative affect toward in vivo testing and openness to alternatives, and highest where oversight and mutual human–animal benefit are made visible.","section":"sec-data-welfare","anchor":"content/03_data_welfare_3rs.md#clm_fa90fc6d45f02c3a","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{}}
{"id":"clm_fbe60c77571900ea","text":"The harm is doubled at the bench, because the animals bred to regenerate lost data are disproportionately animals killed without ever entering an analysis, and euthanising surplus animals is among the strongest reported stressors on the people who must do it.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_fbe60c77571900ea","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"laboratory animals (surplus/euthanasia)","model":"laboratory animals (surplus/euthanasia)","outcome":"moral harm of animal death and human welfare cost"}}
{"id":"clm_fced19a702a030f9","text":"Surveys across Portuguese universities, Amsterdam, and international samples add that admission rises among younger and more prolific researchers and tracks contract type, career stage, and perceived research climate, and a principled taxonomy notes that the most-reported practices are omissions — selective reporting of analyses, citations, and covariates — some of which may under narrow conditions be neutral or even useful.","section":"sec-incentives","anchor":"content/07_incentives.md#clm_fced19a702a030f9","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: likely; scope status: matched.","scope":{"outcome":"QRP-admission predictors; some omissions may be benign under narrow conditions","method":"QRP-determinant surveys and QRP taxonomy"}}
{"id":"clm_fd0a6956653ed15a","text":"The irony runs deeper: the animal reference standard against which NAMs are validated is itself only moderately reproducible, with standardised endocrine assays replicating at 72% and 74% and, as the same review reports, rodent carcinogenicity outcomes agreeing only 65–86% between sexes of one species and 36–74% between rat and mouse, so NAM concordance is being measured against a shaky yardstick — which is precisely why one validation-framework argues concordance with animal data is a scientifically weak anchor and that human relevance, not animal agreement, should be the criterion.","section":"sec-nams-data","anchor":"content/06_nams_data.md#clm_fd0a6956653ed15a","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: limitation; modality: likely; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"rodent carcinogenicity / endocrine bioassays","model":"rodent carcinogenicity / endocrine bioassays","outcome":"human-relevance vs animal-agreement criterion","method":"animal-concordance validation of NAMs"}}
{"id":"clm_fd87f794272837d8","text":"This is not a hopeful addendum to the technical mechanisms; it is their enabling condition, because a virtual control group that no committee will accept, a FAIR mandate that no one checks, and a NAM dataset that earns its author no credit are all instances of the same inert policy.","section":"sec-conclusion","anchor":"content/09_conclusion.md#clm_fd87f794272837d8","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: major_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"regulatory toxicology (VCG)","model":"regulatory toxicology (VCG); FAIR mandates and NAM datasets","outcome":"inert policy as the enabling condition","method":"policy enforcement and author credit; FAIR mandates and NAM datasets"}}
{"id":"clm_fe72265c48d15917","text":"But the field's readiness is contested: proponents argue NAMs are already fit to assure chemical safety in defined settings, while regulatory reviews document continued dependence on animal data for the adversity call, and microphysiological systems remain largely unadopted in regulated decision-making.","section":"sec-introduction","anchor":"content/01_introduction.md#clm_fe72265c48d15917","claimType":"summary","qualification":"Source claim type: review_synthesis; modality: contested; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"NAM/microphysiological systems for chemical safety","model":"NAM/microphysiological systems for chemical safety","outcome":"NAM readiness debate","method":"regulatory readiness and adversity assessment"}}
{"id":"clm_fec85973228eb1e5","text":"One proposal presumes review bodies can and should assess research rigor and expected benefit through a structured benefit-assessment instrument, while an analysis of US committees argues they structurally lack the expertise and mandate to judge scientific merit, so their approval carries no such warranty.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_fec85973228eb1e5","claimType":"other","qualification":"Source claim type: comparative; modality: contested; scope status: minor_difference_qualified.","scope":{"population":"animal research","model":"animal research","outcome":"can ethics review assess scientific merit","method":"benefit-assessment instruments vs committee capacity"}}
{"id":"clm_ffd7a93a04aa6de6","text":"An audit of orthodontic animal studies reported a mean ARRIVE score of 57.9.","section":"sec-governance","anchor":"content/08_governance_pathways.md#clm_ffd7a93a04aa6de6","claimType":"empirical","qualification":"Source claim type: empirical; modality: established; scope status: matched.","scope":{"population":"orthodontic animal studies","model":"orthodontic animal studies","outcome":"reporting quality","method":"ARRIVE reporting audit"}}

